1
00:00:05,534 --> 00:00:07,555
on Wednesday to our session, Rules of the Game,

2
00:00:08,095 --> 00:00:10,655
five further techniques from rather clever designers.

3
00:00:10,695 --> 00:00:12,456
I want to remind everyone to turn off your cell phones

4
00:00:12,496 --> 00:00:13,836
or other noise-making devices.

5
00:00:14,796 --> 00:00:16,277
Remember to fill out your evaluations after.

6
00:00:16,317 --> 00:00:18,437
We really do appreciate the feedback in those.

7
00:00:19,077 --> 00:00:20,298
And this is a session where we get

8
00:00:20,438 --> 00:00:21,918
five illustrious designers to get up

9
00:00:21,938 --> 00:00:23,058
and talk for 10 minutes each

10
00:00:23,698 --> 00:00:25,779
about a rule they use in game design.

11
00:00:26,859 --> 00:00:28,439
We've done this session for a number of years now.

12
00:00:28,479 --> 00:00:30,380
You can go check out some of the previous editions

13
00:00:30,480 --> 00:00:31,020
on The Vault.

14
00:00:31,960 --> 00:00:33,521
Some of them are up on YouTube as well

15
00:00:33,541 --> 00:00:34,281
if you want to see them there.

16
00:00:35,381 --> 00:00:38,683
But what do we mean by game design rules?

17
00:00:38,723 --> 00:00:41,985
You know, I found that some designers are actually sort of resistant to this term,

18
00:00:42,005 --> 00:00:44,267
that there being any sort of rules to game design.

19
00:00:45,047 --> 00:00:47,849
My friend Daniel Cook, when we were talking about it, he said,

20
00:00:48,209 --> 00:00:52,052
you know, rules are highly context-sensitive, rarely make interesting predictions for the project at hand,

21
00:00:52,092 --> 00:00:53,693
and have very little analytical power.

22
00:00:54,093 --> 00:00:55,193
I think he actually wrote that in an email.

23
00:00:55,213 --> 00:00:56,553
He didn't say that in person.

24
00:00:56,633 --> 00:01:00,134
But he didn't think rules were maybe the way to be going.

25
00:01:01,034 --> 00:01:04,775
And Eric Zimmerman, who authored the book Rules of Play

26
00:01:04,835 --> 00:01:06,736
with Katie Salen, doesn't like rules either.

27
00:01:07,116 --> 00:01:08,956
He said, because game designers tend to be

28
00:01:08,996 --> 00:01:10,217
structural analytical thinkers,

29
00:01:10,257 --> 00:01:12,037
coming up with grand sets of rules for good design

30
00:01:12,057 --> 00:01:13,537
is very seductive, including for me.

31
00:01:14,078 --> 00:01:16,138
Over the years, I have tried to cultivate skepticism

32
00:01:16,198 --> 00:01:17,798
towards these kinds of systems.

33
00:01:19,125 --> 00:01:21,987
So why do some people think of these rules as maybe being

34
00:01:22,027 --> 00:01:23,429
too constraining on design?

35
00:01:23,829 --> 00:01:26,251
Well, if we think of the digital games that a lot of us make,

36
00:01:27,332 --> 00:01:29,474
the rules in them tend to be very fixed, very hard,

37
00:01:29,514 --> 00:01:30,595
very fast.

38
00:01:30,656 --> 00:01:32,597
There's only one way you can play the game,

39
00:01:32,637 --> 00:01:35,400
and the computer doesn't really take into account

40
00:01:35,440 --> 00:01:37,242
your feelings when it decides on these rules

41
00:01:38,363 --> 00:01:39,624
and decides on implementing these rules.

42
00:01:39,644 --> 00:01:41,245
And you can't put the Tetris piece anywhere

43
00:01:41,306 --> 00:01:42,627
but where Tetris will let you put it.

44
00:01:43,768 --> 00:01:46,910
Things change a little bit in the board game space.

45
00:01:47,210 --> 00:01:49,671
We've all heard about house rules with Monopoly, right?

46
00:01:49,691 --> 00:01:50,591
Maybe you go over to a friend's house

47
00:01:50,631 --> 00:01:51,732
and they play where you get all the cash

48
00:01:51,752 --> 00:01:52,832
for landing on free parking.

49
00:01:53,192 --> 00:01:55,233
Many other variants that allow the people

50
00:01:55,253 --> 00:01:56,594
who are playing it to have a good time.

51
00:01:57,174 --> 00:01:59,655
You might think chess has a more fixed rule set,

52
00:01:59,715 --> 00:02:02,456
but if you might not have talked to my children about that.

53
00:02:04,478 --> 00:02:06,920
When I was playing with them, I realized

54
00:02:06,940 --> 00:02:08,902
they had worked out a very specific way to handle

55
00:02:10,023 --> 00:02:11,344
when you get your pawn to the other side

56
00:02:11,364 --> 00:02:12,365
and you get back another piece.

57
00:02:12,385 --> 00:02:13,966
And I said, well, that's not really how this rule works.

58
00:02:14,006 --> 00:02:15,187
And they didn't care.

59
00:02:16,428 --> 00:02:21,413
And if anyone has been engaged in intense scrabble games

60
00:02:21,453 --> 00:02:23,815
at friends' houses, often those have very personal rules

61
00:02:23,835 --> 00:02:25,376
to keep them peaceable so they don't

62
00:02:25,417 --> 00:02:26,397
turn into something like this.

63
00:02:27,398 --> 00:02:31,623
You know, I find that, you know, some people get really into their Scrabble and really

64
00:02:31,643 --> 00:02:32,965
into their weird set of rules for it.

65
00:02:33,265 --> 00:02:36,188
I just love that this is the picture you get for Googling Scrabble fight.

66
00:02:38,542 --> 00:02:41,544
But I think even more so when you move into the world of RPGs,

67
00:02:41,584 --> 00:02:43,005
rules become even more malleable.

68
00:02:43,405 --> 00:02:45,967
Like the goal of a DM is to sort of take

69
00:02:45,987 --> 00:02:47,929
the players on a journey, like challenge them enough,

70
00:02:47,969 --> 00:02:50,190
but not too much, not make their death arbitrary

71
00:02:50,251 --> 00:02:53,753
and seem just a result of a bad die roll at the wrong time.

72
00:02:53,833 --> 00:02:56,555
But to give them a chance, to change the rules a little bit

73
00:02:56,595 --> 00:02:58,457
to help them move along in the campaign.

74
00:03:00,085 --> 00:03:03,566
If we think about, too, if we move into a world of sort of art games and things like that,

75
00:03:03,987 --> 00:03:07,568
this can be even more important, like in a game like Brenda Romero's Train, where,

76
00:03:07,909 --> 00:03:09,950
you know, as you realize what the game is doing,

77
00:03:10,390 --> 00:03:14,012
you realize that the deliberately limited rule set allows you to sort of subvert those rules

78
00:03:14,052 --> 00:03:15,873
and try to stop what you realize you're doing.

79
00:03:17,188 --> 00:03:19,690
Now, last year, Luke Muscat did a talk

80
00:03:19,730 --> 00:03:21,731
as a member of this very session, which

81
00:03:21,751 --> 00:03:22,731
I encourage you to go check out.

82
00:03:22,771 --> 00:03:25,392
And he talked about, his whole point was forget rules.

83
00:03:25,432 --> 00:03:25,932
Rules don't matter.

84
00:03:25,972 --> 00:03:26,733
Make goals your game.

85
00:03:26,753 --> 00:03:28,353
That's what you should be giving your team, not rules,

86
00:03:28,393 --> 00:03:28,914
but goals.

87
00:03:30,134 --> 00:03:31,755
And he used slightly more colorful language

88
00:03:31,775 --> 00:03:33,176
when he talked about it in the session.

89
00:03:35,076 --> 00:03:37,538
So I gave my own version of this talk a few years ago

90
00:03:37,598 --> 00:03:38,378
at another conference.

91
00:03:40,539 --> 00:03:43,020
And this was where the talk was called,

92
00:03:43,200 --> 00:03:44,801
What My Parents Taught Me About Game Design.

93
00:03:45,559 --> 00:03:46,980
Now, my parents are not game designers.

94
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:48,721
They haven't really played a lot of games, to be honest,

95
00:03:49,001 --> 00:03:51,864
though my mom is a lifelong, to this day, baseball enthusiast.

96
00:03:53,405 --> 00:03:55,667
But I use this talk as sort of looking

97
00:03:55,687 --> 00:03:57,108
at how they have raised me as parents

98
00:03:57,568 --> 00:03:59,910
and how that informed how I thought about players

99
00:03:59,950 --> 00:04:01,311
and how you treat players in your game.

100
00:04:01,912 --> 00:04:03,473
And this talk is up on YouTube if you

101
00:04:03,513 --> 00:04:04,214
want to go check it out.

102
00:04:05,875 --> 00:04:06,936
But I'll just give you a spoiler.

103
00:04:06,956 --> 00:04:08,857
These were sort of the three principles that I found.

104
00:04:09,878 --> 00:04:11,379
I extracted from how they treated me

105
00:04:11,439 --> 00:04:13,320
and thought of how that's how I end up

106
00:04:13,340 --> 00:04:14,561
treating my players in my games.

107
00:04:15,542 --> 00:04:18,985
And I have a little bit of an addendum to this.

108
00:04:19,505 --> 00:04:21,166
This is a picture that I like because it shows my dad,

109
00:04:21,186 --> 00:04:23,488
but also my long flowing locks from long ago.

110
00:04:25,149 --> 00:04:28,370
And in the last year, my dad actually passed away.

111
00:04:29,071 --> 00:04:31,011
And as I was going through the process

112
00:04:31,171 --> 00:04:33,912
of working on the eulogy and going through memorial service,

113
00:04:34,152 --> 00:04:35,553
I ended up talking to a number of his students.

114
00:04:35,593 --> 00:04:37,314
He was a lifelong psychology professor.

115
00:04:37,874 --> 00:04:40,675
And they said that one thing he always said to them was,

116
00:04:40,975 --> 00:04:42,496
are you asking the right questions?

117
00:04:42,996 --> 00:04:44,656
So let me give you an example of what he meant by that

118
00:04:45,116 --> 00:04:46,457
and how he interacted with me one time.

119
00:04:46,477 --> 00:04:48,438
So he was a lifelong lover of books.

120
00:04:48,498 --> 00:04:50,979
These are several of his favorite books that I now have.

121
00:04:52,339 --> 00:04:55,082
And he talked about this one specific book that he gave me

122
00:04:55,423 --> 00:04:56,043
was Powers of 10.

123
00:04:56,744 --> 00:04:59,147
So somewhere around when I was 8 or 10,

124
00:04:59,347 --> 00:05:01,850
I had asked about the relative size of planets

125
00:05:01,890 --> 00:05:02,551
or something like that.

126
00:05:02,571 --> 00:05:03,952
I don't really remember what the question was.

127
00:05:04,233 --> 00:05:05,274
And he didn't have the answer.

128
00:05:05,474 --> 00:05:07,116
And a couple of days later, he came back with this book

129
00:05:07,156 --> 00:05:07,797
and said, here you go.

130
00:05:07,817 --> 00:05:09,519
And I said, what is this book?

131
00:05:09,539 --> 00:05:10,760
And he's like, well, you're asking about planets.

132
00:05:10,820 --> 00:05:11,341
It's all in there.

133
00:05:11,681 --> 00:05:13,583
So this is a book that's, I don't know,

134
00:05:13,623 --> 00:05:14,844
some of you may be familiar with it.

135
00:05:15,665 --> 00:05:18,728
It's sort of a look at scale in the universe at large, right?

136
00:05:18,828 --> 00:05:21,831
And it goes from a sort of an intergalactic scale

137
00:05:22,231 --> 00:05:24,994
and zooms down more and more at orders of 10

138
00:05:25,294 --> 00:05:27,396
as it gets closer and closer, till it finally

139
00:05:27,476 --> 00:05:30,379
zooms through some guy's hand in a park in Chicago,

140
00:05:30,880 --> 00:05:32,441
and then goes down to the subatomic level.

141
00:05:33,285 --> 00:05:35,727
And again, this wasn't a book really suited to my age

142
00:05:35,767 --> 00:05:37,228
at the time, but it had great pictures.

143
00:05:37,288 --> 00:05:38,009
I found those cool.

144
00:05:38,289 --> 00:05:39,770
And I've kept reading it over the years.

145
00:05:40,010 --> 00:05:42,172
And it sort of just reframed the question.

146
00:05:42,212 --> 00:05:44,493
Again, it was like, well, you're asking about size of planets,

147
00:05:44,573 --> 00:05:45,634
but here I can answer that.

148
00:05:45,734 --> 00:05:47,956
But here's this much more interesting set of questions.

149
00:05:48,376 --> 00:05:50,037
This will expand how you're thinking

150
00:05:50,077 --> 00:05:52,899
about the subjects you're interested in.

151
00:05:53,720 --> 00:05:54,481
So I appreciated that.

152
00:05:54,501 --> 00:05:56,022
I appreciated that he challenged me that way.

153
00:05:56,402 --> 00:05:58,244
And I encourage you, as you're looking at the talks we're

154
00:05:58,264 --> 00:06:01,427
going to have here today, to look at these not necessarily

155
00:06:01,547 --> 00:06:03,989
as a rule you must follow, a rule that is exactly

156
00:06:04,029 --> 00:06:06,051
the answer to your problems, but as something that just helps

157
00:06:06,071 --> 00:06:08,794
you reframe a problem you may be having in game design.

158
00:06:08,834 --> 00:06:11,116
It helps you do the game design work that we all

159
00:06:11,136 --> 00:06:11,936
do in different ways.

160
00:06:12,157 --> 00:06:12,297
Now.

161
00:06:13,147 --> 00:06:17,553
I must confess my inspiration for this intro partly came from seeing Powers of X as a reference

162
00:06:17,633 --> 00:06:18,995
in Sorin's talk coming up.

163
00:06:19,575 --> 00:06:23,941
Aaron will also be asking you if you are asking the right questions of your players.

164
00:06:24,542 --> 00:06:27,866
Later on, Stone will show you how he made a board game for a movie he was too young

165
00:06:27,886 --> 00:06:31,871
to actually see, while Josh will tell you why he likes to write only half a story.

166
00:06:32,692 --> 00:06:34,754
But first, we have Raph Koster.

167
00:06:35,174 --> 00:06:38,217
Raph Koster is widely known for his work in online games,

168
00:06:38,237 --> 00:06:39,538
going back to MUDs.

169
00:06:40,399 --> 00:06:42,020
Since then, he went on to work on some

170
00:06:42,040 --> 00:06:44,903
of the first commercial MMOs in Ultima Online, later Star Wars

171
00:06:44,923 --> 00:06:45,304
Galaxy.

172
00:06:45,324 --> 00:06:46,965
He now works as an independent designer

173
00:06:47,005 --> 00:06:49,367
in a wide range of games, both digital and analog,

174
00:06:49,848 --> 00:06:51,169
and a variety of game-related projects.

175
00:06:51,189 --> 00:06:52,250
I give you Raph Koster.

176
00:07:02,784 --> 00:07:02,824
Hi.

177
00:07:04,665 --> 00:07:07,546
So this is like my little rule.

178
00:07:07,566 --> 00:07:10,687
It doesn't really necessarily mean what it says.

179
00:07:13,609 --> 00:07:16,010
This is an idea I've had more than once, right?

180
00:07:16,050 --> 00:07:19,812
Like literally, I've now made four or five games

181
00:07:19,852 --> 00:07:21,533
about trying to capture the feeling

182
00:07:21,553 --> 00:07:23,053
of playing a kaleidoscope.

183
00:07:25,768 --> 00:07:29,272
The thing about an idea like that is that it can really kind of go either way.

184
00:07:29,392 --> 00:07:34,337
It can be about the math of kaleidoscopes, like how they tumble, or it can be about the

185
00:07:34,397 --> 00:07:41,024
sensation of a kaleidoscope, like the human experience of tumbling or being lost in a

186
00:07:41,064 --> 00:07:41,544
landscape.

187
00:07:43,375 --> 00:07:45,517
I'd like to say you can start from either end, right?

188
00:07:45,537 --> 00:07:48,300
I mean, have a strong idea for a game system,

189
00:07:48,320 --> 00:07:50,862
a set of mathematical relationships,

190
00:07:51,403 --> 00:07:55,227
a set of dynamics, or maybe you have a really strong narrative

191
00:07:55,327 --> 00:07:58,090
or experiential idea, and that's fine.

192
00:07:58,190 --> 00:08:02,094
Different designers often have really different tendencies,

193
00:08:02,174 --> 00:08:02,454
right?

194
00:08:02,495 --> 00:08:04,336
They'll start from one end or the other.

195
00:08:05,489 --> 00:08:07,250
And that's perfectly fine.

196
00:08:07,390 --> 00:08:12,272
Like, often board game designers start maybe with a bias towards the systems end.

197
00:08:12,932 --> 00:08:17,414
And certainly AAA games often start with a bias towards the experience end,

198
00:08:17,554 --> 00:08:19,855
art games, many indie games.

199
00:08:20,055 --> 00:08:21,295
And we'd never say...

200
00:08:22,035 --> 00:08:25,238
hey, you can reskin this Telltale game any way you want

201
00:08:25,458 --> 00:08:27,079
and think that we still end up with anything

202
00:08:27,359 --> 00:08:29,741
that we'd call the same game.

203
00:08:29,781 --> 00:08:31,222
The experience wouldn't be intact.

204
00:08:31,322 --> 00:08:33,584
But we'd also, we wouldn't say, hey,

205
00:08:33,624 --> 00:08:35,205
let's swap out the conflict resolution

206
00:08:35,245 --> 00:08:37,107
mechanic in poker either and think

207
00:08:37,147 --> 00:08:38,748
that poker remains intact.

208
00:08:38,788 --> 00:08:40,949
I mean, it changes it substantially.

209
00:08:42,531 --> 00:08:46,032
Starting with either end, then, they're both super valid,

210
00:08:46,653 --> 00:08:49,514
since by the time you're done, you really

211
00:08:49,554 --> 00:08:52,275
kind of need to have both ideas in place.

212
00:08:52,495 --> 00:08:54,596
You really need to have your experience and your system

213
00:08:54,656 --> 00:08:55,616
idea in place.

214
00:08:57,417 --> 00:09:01,298
Because after all, almost no games are purely experiences

215
00:09:01,378 --> 00:09:02,759
or purely abstract.

216
00:09:02,839 --> 00:09:04,500
It's just rarely a thing.

217
00:09:06,798 --> 00:09:08,880
But starting from one end to the other

218
00:09:08,940 --> 00:09:10,942
does have a whole bunch of implications.

219
00:09:11,423 --> 00:09:13,044
And certainly in my experience, I've

220
00:09:13,104 --> 00:09:15,366
found it's really important to move towards the middle

221
00:09:15,446 --> 00:09:16,187
pretty quickly.

222
00:09:16,928 --> 00:09:20,751
Like let's say you start from the system, which I often do,

223
00:09:20,811 --> 00:09:22,573
especially because I'm doing a lot of tabletop work

224
00:09:22,613 --> 00:09:22,993
these days.

225
00:09:23,974 --> 00:09:25,916
If you don't move to the middle, you

226
00:09:25,956 --> 00:09:28,418
can pretty quickly get stuck with an abstract game, which

227
00:09:28,679 --> 00:09:31,041
FYI, abstract tabletop games are really hard to market.

228
00:09:33,295 --> 00:09:35,698
You might end up with like really simplistic narrative.

229
00:09:35,738 --> 00:09:39,503
This is how you end up with, okay, so we'll provide the experience by wedging cut scenes

230
00:09:39,543 --> 00:09:44,751
in between levels of something, you know, that kind of really simple way of providing

231
00:09:44,791 --> 00:09:45,051
something.

232
00:09:46,829 --> 00:09:52,273
Finding an experience or a metaphor that fits the system quickly is a better path,

233
00:09:52,353 --> 00:09:57,757
even though a strong system idea can usually be skinned in a lot of ways, right?

234
00:09:57,777 --> 00:10:02,420
Like, think of chess sets, for example, from Lord of the Rings to, you know,

235
00:10:02,460 --> 00:10:06,723
I think in Theory of Fun I said chess boards designed around different types of snot, right?

236
00:10:06,823 --> 00:10:08,084
You can play chess with all of those.

237
00:10:08,424 --> 00:10:09,044
It's all good.

238
00:10:09,705 --> 00:10:11,266
Well, maybe not the snot, but you know.

239
00:10:12,286 --> 00:10:17,051
So if you start, though, from the narrative or experiential

240
00:10:17,171 --> 00:10:20,334
end of things, there are pitfalls starting there, too,

241
00:10:20,674 --> 00:10:20,934
right?

242
00:10:21,395 --> 00:10:24,398
If you don't ever get around to developing a systemic core.

243
00:10:24,418 --> 00:10:27,040
One of the biggest is your game's consumable,

244
00:10:27,280 --> 00:10:29,623
and these days it might get consumed on Twitch

245
00:10:30,123 --> 00:10:32,145
long before it gets played at all, right?

246
00:10:32,205 --> 00:10:33,927
So that's a real risk these days.

247
00:10:34,808 --> 00:10:38,853
you often have to spend disproportionately on content.

248
00:10:39,714 --> 00:10:43,359
You might end up making tons of small mini games.

249
00:10:43,699 --> 00:10:45,601
And of course, each of those is still a game

250
00:10:45,641 --> 00:10:46,643
that you have to balance.

251
00:10:46,763 --> 00:10:49,326
So it multiplies your testing time.

252
