00:22:51,171 --> 00:22:52,852
And once we started asking that question,

502
00:22:52,972 --> 00:22:54,153
everything started getting easier.

503
00:22:55,053 --> 00:22:58,374
And then we ultimately did make a game that teachers loved.

504
00:22:58,554 --> 00:22:59,834
Partly they already loved it, it's a great game.

505
00:23:00,154 --> 00:23:03,095
But also it gave them a way to bring it into classrooms in a

506
00:23:03,135 --> 00:23:05,396
way that they hadn't been able to do before and it became

507
00:23:05,576 --> 00:23:06,216
quite popular.

508
00:23:06,556 --> 00:23:08,777
And then we actually were trying to do data analysis to

509
00:23:09,357 --> 00:23:11,458
try to actually turn SimCity into a test of sorts.

510
00:23:11,498 --> 00:23:12,578
It was kind of a terrible idea.

511
00:23:12,618 --> 00:23:15,039
But when you look at the data that was coming out of

512
00:23:15,059 --> 00:23:17,819
SimCity, it was just this torrent of stuff that our

513
00:23:17,859 --> 00:23:19,480
assessment experts could make no sense of

514
00:23:19,540 --> 00:23:20,640
because it's so massive.

515
00:23:21,100 --> 00:23:24,202
And so with our next game, we decided to start with the question at the core.

516
00:23:24,582 --> 00:23:26,003
First we started with what should we teach?

517
00:23:26,303 --> 00:23:29,164
We did this big meta-analysis, our learning designers attacked this, and

518
00:23:29,204 --> 00:23:30,845
they eventually came up with argumentation.

519
00:23:31,245 --> 00:23:33,506
Because it's under-taught, it's a leverage point, it's new,

520
00:23:33,566 --> 00:23:34,867
teachers don't really know how to teach it.

521
00:23:35,427 --> 00:23:39,249
And from there, we asked the question, what is the single most important thing we

522
00:23:39,269 --> 00:23:41,330
could teach a sixth grader about argumentation?

523
00:23:41,730 --> 00:23:43,652
And that question is at the heart of this game.

524
00:23:43,712 --> 00:23:44,973
The mechanics are built from it.

525
00:23:45,313 --> 00:23:46,774
Everything that we ask the player to do

526
00:23:47,094 --> 00:23:49,957
is intended to perform the question of whether or not

527
00:23:49,997 --> 00:23:52,279
they understand that, which means the game from its core

528
00:23:52,299 --> 00:23:52,999
is built that way.

529
00:23:53,520 --> 00:23:54,981
And then we used a pre and post test.

530
00:23:55,161 --> 00:23:57,183
There's this idea, of course, from science, from education,

531
00:23:57,223 --> 00:23:59,445
but it's something that you can do with a game, where you test

532
00:23:59,565 --> 00:24:00,826
where the player is when they start,

533
00:24:01,046 --> 00:24:03,088
you get them to play the game, you test to the other side.

534
00:24:03,468 --> 00:24:05,009
And then you can iterate and discover

535
00:24:05,049 --> 00:24:06,451
whether you're actually achieving your goals.

536
00:24:07,011 --> 00:24:09,573
The end result was a statistically significant

537
00:24:09,653 --> 00:24:12,314
improvement in the kids' understanding of

538
00:24:12,354 --> 00:24:12,995
argumentation.

539
00:24:13,015 --> 00:24:15,596
And this was also validated against an external measure.

540
00:24:16,057 --> 00:24:18,858
So we had a separate test that we knew was already a valid

541
00:24:18,898 --> 00:24:21,140
measurement of argumentation, stood our game up next to it,

542
00:24:21,440 --> 00:24:22,881
and found a statistical increase.

543
00:24:23,221 --> 00:24:25,102
I want to linger on that for a second, because this is the

544
00:24:25,322 --> 00:24:27,644
young lady's illustrated primer, if you're familiar

545
00:24:27,724 --> 00:24:28,745
with Neil Stephenson.

546
00:24:29,125 --> 00:24:31,887
This is the interactive object, which is infinitely

547
00:24:31,967 --> 00:24:33,828
replicable, which can lift people up.

548
00:24:34,068 --> 00:24:34,828
through education.

549
00:24:34,908 --> 00:24:36,469
And I think that's a really powerful idea.

550
00:24:36,529 --> 00:24:38,130
I hope that we make a lot more games this way.

551
00:24:38,870 --> 00:24:39,831
So back to playtesting.

552
00:24:39,871 --> 00:24:42,632
If you Google what you should ask when you playtest, you get

553
00:24:42,672 --> 00:24:44,093
this kind of series of horrifying

554
00:24:44,133 --> 00:24:45,093
questions from the internet.

555
00:24:45,433 --> 00:24:48,034
At the end of the day, it's like, was it fun?

556
00:24:48,055 --> 00:24:50,135
There's lots of variations on, was it fun?

557
00:24:50,496 --> 00:24:52,156
And I have a lot of problems with that question.

558
00:24:52,717 --> 00:24:54,238
Some better questions are things more like,

559
00:24:54,738 --> 00:24:55,599
how should the player feel?

560
00:24:55,919 --> 00:24:57,620
And these are questions that you have to ask yourself,

561
00:24:57,780 --> 00:25:00,182
because in the process of discovering the right questions

562
00:25:00,202 --> 00:25:01,242
that you need to ask players,

563
00:25:01,422 --> 00:25:03,324
you have to ask yourself the right questions

564
00:25:03,364 --> 00:25:04,284
about what you're even making.

565
00:25:04,364 --> 00:25:05,645
Because most of the time when we start,

566
00:25:05,965 --> 00:25:07,386
we don't ask that question of ourselves

567
00:25:07,446 --> 00:25:08,447
as precisely as we should.

568
00:25:09,591 --> 00:25:12,013
So the usual play testing questions we tend to ask are

569
00:25:12,033 --> 00:25:13,714
categorized as stupid questions and

570
00:25:13,754 --> 00:25:14,615
usability questions.

571
00:25:14,875 --> 00:25:16,896
The usability questions are actually really useful.

572
00:25:16,916 --> 00:25:19,078
The game needs to be usable, software has to be usable.

573
00:25:19,558 --> 00:25:21,860
But we ask these dumb questions about what part the

574
00:25:21,880 --> 00:25:22,561
player likes best.

575
00:25:22,861 --> 00:25:25,903
The real problem with a question like this is that

576
00:25:26,003 --> 00:25:27,344
what you say is, was it fun?

577
00:25:27,724 --> 00:25:30,927
And what they hear is, please validate my existence, I might

578
00:25:30,967 --> 00:25:31,888
kill myself if you don't.

579
00:25:32,288 --> 00:25:35,049
They know what you're asking, and they see right through you.

580
00:25:35,069 --> 00:25:36,489
So they're going to start gaming that question.

581
00:25:36,809 --> 00:25:39,610
Binary questions are usually a bad idea with play testers

582
00:25:39,670 --> 00:25:41,591
because they're going to try to find what you think

583
00:25:41,611 --> 00:25:42,411
the right answer is.

584
00:25:43,191 --> 00:25:44,572
And I would say about usability, though,

585
00:25:44,592 --> 00:25:45,792
you do have to fix the usability.

586
00:25:45,832 --> 00:25:46,993
The game has to be accessible.

587
00:25:47,053 --> 00:25:48,953
It has to be accessible to a specific audience

588
00:25:48,973 --> 00:25:49,994
that you're intending to strike.

589
00:25:50,514 --> 00:25:53,535
And in SimCity EDU, we actually had that problem in particular

590
00:25:53,595 --> 00:25:56,116
because students of middle school age

591
00:25:56,156 --> 00:25:58,556
were not necessarily the intended audience of SimCity.

592
00:25:58,576 --> 00:25:59,737
So there were a lot of adaptations

593
00:25:59,757 --> 00:26:00,577
we had to make for that.

594
00:26:01,600 --> 00:26:05,862
At the end of the day, what we were trying to do with SimCity EDU was actually, and Mars Generation 1,

595
00:26:06,362 --> 00:26:10,545
a lot easier than what we have to do with commercial games because our objective was so precise

596
00:26:10,765 --> 00:26:12,546
and we could just measure it and iterate against it.

597
00:26:12,906 --> 00:26:16,228
What we're trying to do with video games is a lot more abstract than expressive.

598
00:26:16,248 --> 00:26:17,989
That's a hard thing to get a question around.

599
00:26:18,529 --> 00:26:21,051
But I think that if you break down the idea of what fun is,

600
00:26:21,351 --> 00:26:24,633
you can look at it through the lens of what specific emotions are being created.

601
00:26:24,993 --> 00:26:27,395
What are the experiences that we want to evoke in a player?

602
00:26:27,735 --> 00:26:29,516
And if you throw this sort of palette at them,

603
00:26:29,956 --> 00:26:34,037
Then it gives you a razor against which to measure your intent versus what the player

604
00:26:34,077 --> 00:26:35,218
is actually experiencing.

605
00:26:35,378 --> 00:26:36,718
So it gives you something testable.

606
00:26:37,158 --> 00:26:39,159
We did this in Mars Generation 1 a little bit.

607
00:26:39,439 --> 00:26:44,520
We mapped where the player would start emotionally and then where we wanted them to end up emotionally

608
00:26:44,540 --> 00:26:47,601
and then we attached that to the idea of the competency itself.

609
00:26:47,921 --> 00:26:51,162
So there's a transformation that we wanted to bring about that was purely emotional because

610
00:26:51,202 --> 00:26:52,783
we knew that that's what games do.

611
00:26:52,823 --> 00:26:54,643
They actually evoke feelings, all media do.

612
00:26:55,738 --> 00:26:58,606
So I would say that what you do is identify the emotional

613
00:26:58,626 --> 00:27:00,953
transformation that you want to bring about in the player.

614
00:27:01,294 --> 00:27:03,400
And that starts with asking yourself the right questions.

615
00:27:04,198 --> 00:27:06,239
The questions of what is my real intent?

616
00:27:06,899 --> 00:27:08,139
What is the outcome that I want?

617
00:27:08,539 --> 00:27:10,620
Is the intent that I have actually precise?

618
00:27:10,960 --> 00:27:12,160
If I create these emotions,

619
00:27:12,240 --> 00:27:13,781
is that unlike anything I've ever seen

620
00:27:13,841 --> 00:27:15,121
or does it remind me of something else?

621
00:27:15,441 --> 00:27:17,342
There's a lot of questions in that process.

622
00:27:17,742 --> 00:27:19,822
Then you can actually create a pre and post test

623
00:27:19,902 --> 00:27:21,583
or at least a series of survey questions

624
00:27:21,603 --> 00:27:23,303
if you don't want to think about it that scientifically

625
00:27:23,623 --> 00:27:26,044
about what you're gonna ask players in order to reveal

626
00:27:26,304 --> 00:27:27,744
how will I know that they're feeling

627
00:27:27,764 --> 00:27:28,585
what I want them to feel?

628
00:27:28,725 --> 00:27:30,305
Because emotions are really hard to pin down.

629
00:27:30,965 --> 00:27:34,648
And I would just linger on that for a moment too, to say you can use pre and post tests

630
00:27:34,968 --> 00:27:38,410
in video game development. This is something that I don't think I've ever heard talked about,

631
00:27:38,450 --> 00:27:42,632
but it's something that we can do, measuring both where they start as well as where they end up,

632
00:27:42,912 --> 00:27:45,334
as opposed to just asking them at the end whether they liked it or not.

633
00:27:46,274 --> 00:27:47,335
So again, good questions.

634
00:27:47,695 --> 00:27:49,975
What is the core emotion and the core emotional blend?

635
00:27:50,356 --> 00:27:51,956
Is that blend unique?

636
00:27:52,396 --> 00:27:55,497
And do my mechanics perform the feeling of that by themselves?

637
00:27:55,938 --> 00:27:57,798
If they don't, they're probably the wrong mechanics.

638
00:27:58,398 --> 00:28:00,339
And then for players, what were you feeling?

639
00:28:00,939 --> 00:28:01,820
What does this remind you of?

640
00:28:02,160 --> 00:28:03,240
It's a whole little bit sideways.

641
00:28:03,601 --> 00:28:04,341
It's not direct.

642
00:28:04,401 --> 00:28:06,042
Because you ask a direct question, they're going to

643
00:28:06,082 --> 00:28:08,303
game the question, which people who design the SAT

644
00:28:08,323 --> 00:28:09,184
certainly know as well.

645
00:28:10,024 --> 00:28:12,025
I would say as a warning that this can be a habit forming

646
00:28:12,065 --> 00:28:12,486
process.

647
00:28:12,766 --> 00:28:13,446
I hope that it is.

648
00:28:13,606 --> 00:28:15,567
Because once you start to look at your game this way, with

649
00:28:15,667 --> 00:28:18,409
this level of precision efficacy, it can become a

650
00:28:18,449 --> 00:28:21,451
transformative process for your own development process.

651
00:28:21,991 --> 00:28:24,732
And I would also say that it's okay to iterate the pre and

652
00:28:24,752 --> 00:28:25,212
post test.

653
00:28:25,553 --> 00:28:27,833
Something that I think we didn't realize was that if you

654
00:28:27,853 --> 00:28:29,754
start out with the wrong questions, we thought, oh,

655
00:28:29,994 --> 00:28:30,395
we're screwed.

656
00:28:30,415 --> 00:28:30,915
That's terrible.

657
00:28:31,235 --> 00:28:31,635
It's not.

658
00:28:31,735 --> 00:28:34,256
Part of the process of the process of using these

659
00:28:34,296 --> 00:28:36,857
questions is to sharpen your idea of your intent.

660
00:28:37,157 --> 00:28:38,958
So you can change the questions and then keep

661
00:28:39,038 --> 00:28:39,738
working against them.

662
00:28:41,079 --> 00:28:41,679
And that's it.

663
00:28:41,979 --> 00:28:42,620
Thank you very much.

664
00:28:52,904 --> 00:28:55,926
Next up, we have someone who is most known for perhaps

665
00:28:55,946 --> 00:28:58,707
for his involvements with Civilizations 3 and 4.

666
00:28:59,588 --> 00:29:01,569
He now runs indie studio Mohawk Games,

667
00:29:01,689 --> 00:29:05,411
who shipped not that long ago Economic RTS Off-World Trading

668
00:29:05,471 --> 00:29:08,432
Company and recently announced their next game is 10 Crowns.

669
00:29:08,692 --> 00:29:10,873
He's also on the advisory board for this very conference,

670
00:29:10,894 --> 00:29:12,274
so you can direct your complaints to him.

671
00:29:12,674 --> 00:29:13,755
I give you Soren Johnson.

672
00:29:16,036 --> 00:29:16,957
Thank you.

673
00:29:17,037 --> 00:29:21,339
Hey, everybody.

674
00:29:23,841 --> 00:29:27,125
All right, so three strikes and you're out.

675
00:29:28,027 --> 00:29:30,731
This phrase is so common, it's basically an idiom.

676
00:29:30,931 --> 00:29:32,914
Indeed, while some of our non-American friends here

677
00:29:32,994 --> 00:29:34,797
might be baffled by baseball in general,

678
00:29:35,157 --> 00:29:36,740
they probably still know this rule.

679
00:29:37,020 --> 00:29:37,341
However.

680
00:29:38,558 --> 00:29:39,499
It's not actually true.

681
00:29:40,159 --> 00:29:42,720
The batter is not out after the third strike.

682
00:29:42,961 --> 00:29:44,621
It's only when the catcher catches the ball

683
00:29:45,162 --> 00:29:46,442
that the batter is out.

684
00:29:46,902 --> 00:29:48,723
If the catcher drops or misses the pitch,

685
00:29:49,003 --> 00:29:50,864
then the batter is not out and has a chance

686
00:29:50,884 --> 00:29:51,805
to advance to first.

687
00:29:52,445 --> 00:29:54,066
This almost always results in an out

688
00:29:54,226 --> 00:29:55,766
as the catcher simply picks up the ball

689
00:29:55,826 --> 00:29:56,727
and makes the easy throw.

690
00:29:57,167 --> 00:29:58,708
But occasionally, this little-known rule

691
00:29:58,748 --> 00:30:01,629
can become a big deal, as it did in last year's final game

692
00:30:01,669 --> 00:30:03,750
in the playoff series between the Chicago Cubs

693
00:30:03,890 --> 00:30:04,931
and the Washington Nationals.

694
00:30:05,591 --> 00:30:09,794
Max Scherzer threw a third strike past a swinging Javier Baez, but watch what happens.

695
00:30:13,056 --> 00:30:17,879
The Nationals catcher Matt Wieters missed the ball between his legs, allowing Baez to safely

696
00:30:17,919 --> 00:30:22,202
make it to first base. This would have been the third out of the inning. Instead, the Cubs scored

697
00:30:22,242 --> 00:30:26,865
two more runs and later won the game by only one run in advance to the next round. Thus,

698
00:30:27,065 --> 00:30:31,668
an obscure rule knocked the Nationals out of the playoffs. Where exactly did this rule come from?

699
00:30:33,775 --> 00:30:36,156
It actually reaches back to the very first time

700
00:30:36,196 --> 00:30:38,136
the rules of baseball were put down in print

701
00:30:38,436 --> 00:30:41,817
by the German Johann Christoph Friedrich Gutsmuth.

702
00:30:42,657 --> 00:30:44,958
He outlined something called English baseball, which

703
00:30:44,998 --> 00:30:48,339
was a game of innings with a batter, fielders, safe bases,

704
00:30:48,399 --> 00:30:49,359
and scoring at home plate.

705
00:30:49,759 --> 00:30:51,820
However, there were no strikes or balls yet.

706
00:30:52,340 --> 00:30:53,900
The pitcher stood close to the batter

707
00:30:54,220 --> 00:30:57,141
and more or less delivered the ball as a soft lob to be hit.

708
00:30:57,641 --> 00:30:59,441
The pitcher wasn't trying to challenge the batter.

709
00:30:59,802 --> 00:31:01,982
The game was about fielding the ball after it had been hit.

710
00:31:02,622 --> 00:31:06,145
However, what happens when there is a terrible batter who

711
00:31:06,185 --> 00:31:06,925
can't hit anything?

712
00:31:08,026 --> 00:31:09,967
In Gutsmith's game, he has special rule for this

713
00:31:09,987 --> 00:31:13,510
situation. On the third swing, the ball is automatically in

714
00:31:13,550 --> 00:31:14,950
play, whether it's hit or not.

715
00:31:15,431 --> 00:31:21,035
So the batter will run to first either after hitting the

716
00:31:21,075 --> 00:31:22,556
ball or missing for the third time.

717
00:31:22,876 --> 00:31:25,037
Indeed, there is no catcher to receive the ball, so the

718
00:31:25,057 --> 00:31:27,139
pitcher would need to run to home plate to pick it up and

719
00:31:27,179 --> 00:31:27,699
throw to first.

720
00:31:29,872 --> 00:31:32,674
In 1845, the American Knickerbocker Baseball Club

721
00:31:32,734 --> 00:31:34,095
writes down their rules for the game,

722
00:31:34,195 --> 00:31:35,215
and some things have changed.

723
00:31:35,776 --> 00:31:38,037
The pitcher is now much farther from the batter

724
00:31:38,177 --> 00:31:39,958
and throws the ball horizontally,

725
00:31:40,398 --> 00:31:42,119
which requires the new position of catcher.

726
00:31:42,700 --> 00:31:45,361
However, they preserve the logic of the old gutsmith's rule,

727
00:31:45,781 --> 00:31:48,023
that the ball's in play after the third miss swing,

728
00:31:48,443 --> 00:31:50,024
like old legacy code lying around.

729
00:31:50,424 --> 00:31:52,645
The strikeout is actually emergent gameplay

730
00:31:52,705 --> 00:31:53,886
because after the third miss,

731
00:31:54,246 --> 00:31:55,907
the ball is now technically in play,

732
00:31:56,248 --> 00:31:57,548
and the catcher turns it into an out

733
00:31:57,728 --> 00:31:58,729
by simply catching the pitch.

734
00:32:00,039 --> 00:32:02,541
Thus, there is no actual difference between the catcher

735
00:32:03,182 --> 00:32:04,684
making it out from catching a pop-up

736
00:32:04,844 --> 00:32:06,746
and the catcher making it out from catching the pitch

737
00:32:06,906 --> 00:32:08,007
after a third missed swing.

738
00:32:08,548 --> 00:32:10,270
In each case, the ball is now live,

739
00:32:10,430 --> 00:32:12,292
and the catcher makes it out by catching the ball

740
00:32:12,332 --> 00:32:13,093
before it hits the ground.

741
00:32:14,439 --> 00:32:17,382
However, they had to patch the game later on because of an

742
00:32:17,482 --> 00:32:19,964
unintended consequence of not taking the time to make the

743
00:32:20,004 --> 00:32:22,106
strikeout an official rule.

744
00:32:22,526 --> 00:32:24,888
Because the ball would be considered live after a third

745
00:32:24,929 --> 00:32:27,191
strike, the possibility for a cheesy double or

746
00:32:27,231 --> 00:32:28,171
triple play existed.

747
00:32:28,632 --> 00:32:31,234
For example, if the bases are loaded, then the catcher can

748
00:32:31,274 --> 00:32:35,858
intentionally drop the ball, pick it up again, step on home

749
00:32:35,878 --> 00:32:38,481
plate for an easy out, and then throw to third, and then

750
00:32:38,561 --> 00:32:39,622
onto second for two more.

751
00:32:40,362 --> 00:32:45,026
Therefore, in 1887, they added a new rule so that the batter would automatically be

752
00:32:45,146 --> 00:32:50,750
out if a runner was on first base and there were less than two outs.

753
00:32:51,191 --> 00:32:55,974
Thus, three strikes and you're out, the way everyone assumes baseball is played, is true,

754
00:32:56,575 --> 00:32:59,097
but only under a very specific set of circumstances.

755
00:32:59,597 --> 00:33:03,320
They opted for an ugly patch instead of just rewriting the rules to match how the game

756
00:33:03,340 --> 00:33:04,321
was actually being played.

757
00:33:06,090 --> 00:33:08,372
Indeed, think about the situation with Javier Baez.

758
00:33:08,672 --> 00:33:10,253
There was a runner on first base.

759
00:33:10,573 --> 00:33:12,174
So even though the catcher dropped the ball,

760
00:33:12,194 --> 00:33:15,216
it should have been a strikeout, except there were two outs.

761
00:33:15,476 --> 00:33:17,457
So now we're back to the original drop third strike

762
00:33:17,497 --> 00:33:17,898
rule again.

763
00:33:18,578 --> 00:33:18,998
Think about it.

764
00:33:19,018 --> 00:33:20,319
They could have just rewritten the rule

765
00:33:20,359 --> 00:33:22,781
so that three strikes and you're out applies at all times.

766
00:33:22,841 --> 00:33:24,802
Wouldn't that be simpler, more intuitive?

767
00:33:25,182 --> 00:33:27,684
Why go to the trouble of fixing the one glaring issue

768
00:33:27,724 --> 00:33:29,505
with catchers intentionally dropping the ball

769
00:33:29,605 --> 00:33:31,966
and not just get rid of the old vestigial rule?

770
00:33:34,535 --> 00:33:37,397
The reason is that we inherit our game design from everything

771
00:33:37,417 --> 00:33:38,477
that comes before us.

772
00:33:39,038 --> 00:33:40,979
Sometimes this inheritance is obvious.

773
00:33:41,379 --> 00:33:44,921
Civ 6 inherited from Civ 5, which inherited from Civ 4,

774
00:33:45,001 --> 00:33:45,541
and so on.

775
00:33:47,142 --> 00:33:49,443
Sometimes a designer inherits from the games

776
00:33:49,863 --> 00:33:50,944
he or she played as a kid.

777
00:33:51,584 --> 00:33:53,925
Mario led to Braid, Myst led to The Witness.

778
00:33:55,942 --> 00:33:57,564
Sometimes games inherit from themselves.

779
00:33:58,244 --> 00:34:01,467
This is a timeline of the development of our economic RTS,

780
00:34:01,527 --> 00:34:02,388
Off-Road Trading Company,

781
00:34:03,428 --> 00:34:05,650
and you might make certain development shortcuts

782
00:34:05,690 --> 00:34:06,791
or hacks early on,

783
00:34:07,151 --> 00:34:08,993
just so that you can get your prototype playable.

784
00:34:09,433 --> 00:34:12,296
But then these assumptions are now baked into your design,

785
00:34:12,336 --> 00:34:13,497
whether you want them there or not.

786
00:34:13,857 --> 00:34:16,119
You have to remember that it was an accidental

787
00:34:16,179 --> 00:34:17,040
or arbitrary choice.

788
00:34:19,524 --> 00:34:21,245
The most common thing to inherit, however,

789
00:34:21,405 --> 00:34:24,045
is game mechanics, usually from the games in the same genre.

790
00:34:24,446 --> 00:34:27,186
For example, although Offroad Trading Company is an RTS,

791
00:34:27,346 --> 00:34:29,047
it's notable for being one without units.

792
00:34:29,807 --> 00:34:31,928
However, we didn't start there, as we inherited

793
00:34:31,948 --> 00:34:34,989
from all the other RTSs before us, StarCraft, Age of Empires,

794
00:34:35,029 --> 00:34:35,529
and so on.

795
00:34:36,149 --> 00:34:39,250
Thus, we had scouts, builders, transports, pirate ships,

796
00:34:39,330 --> 00:34:40,290
police ships, and so on.

797
00:34:42,585 --> 00:34:46,990
Over time, we discovered that this inheritance was weighing the game down, forcing the player

798
00:34:47,030 --> 00:34:50,414
to spend time wrangling units that would have been better spent playing the market.

799
00:34:50,974 --> 00:34:52,937
Slowly, we took these units out one by one.

800
00:34:53,317 --> 00:34:57,321
First the transports, then the combat units, then the builders, and finally the scouts.

801
00:34:58,082 --> 00:35:01,646
The game looks like a radical break with the past, but it took us a long time to get there.

802
00:35:03,672 --> 00:35:06,093
The problem is that iterative design can be a trap,

803
00:35:06,493 --> 00:35:08,774
that you can no longer see those parts of your game

804
00:35:08,814 --> 00:35:11,034
that are holding you back from a much better design.

805
00:35:11,695 --> 00:35:12,955
It's easier to make small changes

806
00:35:12,995 --> 00:35:15,556
that fix glaring issues, rather than to re-evaluate

807
00:35:15,596 --> 00:35:16,416
your entire design.

808
00:35:18,717 --> 00:35:20,557
Sometimes, a problem with a game's inheritance

809
00:35:20,657 --> 00:35:22,278
can be at the conceptual level.

810
00:35:22,918 --> 00:35:23,818
Consider Spore.

811
00:35:24,901 --> 00:35:26,822
which was conceived of as a powers of 10 game

812
00:35:27,042 --> 00:35:28,963
that went from cellular scale all the way up

813
00:35:28,983 --> 00:35:29,823
to galactic scale.

814
00:35:30,223 --> 00:35:32,024
That was the hook, the point of making the game.

815
00:35:32,964 --> 00:35:35,185
This part of the game was widely seen as a disappointment,

816
00:35:35,425 --> 00:35:37,186
that the five disparate levels felt like

817
00:35:37,286 --> 00:35:38,906
five different games duct taped together.

818
00:35:39,787 --> 00:35:41,527
However, something interesting happened

819
00:35:41,547 --> 00:35:42,608
with the failure of Spore,

820
00:35:43,948 --> 00:35:46,009
which is that it wasn't actually a failure after all.

821
00:35:46,769 --> 00:35:48,710
This is how many people are playing Spore right now,

822
00:35:49,070 --> 00:35:50,751
which is not bad for a 10 year old game.

823
00:35:52,222 --> 00:35:56,044
In fact, check out this chart which compares Spore to the two most successful PC games

824
00:35:56,104 --> 00:35:57,005
released that same year, 2008.

825
00:35:57,385 --> 00:36:03,209
Spore currently outpaces them both, and keep in mind that Spore didn't even launch on Steam.

826
00:36:04,650 --> 00:36:08,293
What happened was that the most interesting part of the game did not come from the Power

827
00:36:08,453 --> 00:36:12,716
X concept, but from the editors inside the game, especially the creature creator, which

828
00:36:12,756 --> 00:36:14,858
dynamically animated the player's creations.

829
00:36:16,470 --> 00:36:19,012
However, these editors were developed midway through the project.

830
00:36:19,332 --> 00:36:22,975
Maxis started making a game about one thing and accidentally ended up making a game about

831
00:36:23,015 --> 00:36:23,475
something else.

832
00:36:24,356 --> 00:36:28,079
One of the big unanswered questions about Spore is what could we have done if we had

833
00:36:28,099 --> 00:36:31,921
been able to ditch the powers of ten concept and refocus the game on the editors?

834
00:36:34,725 --> 00:36:37,587
So here's a classic case study in inheriting bad design.

835
00:36:38,348 --> 00:36:40,570
Creep denial is a mechanic in the original Dota

836
00:36:40,710 --> 00:36:43,332
where you kill your own units to keep your opponent

837
00:36:43,352 --> 00:36:44,933
from getting gold and experience from them.

838
00:36:45,773 --> 00:36:47,655
Indeed, creep denial is one of the focal points

839
00:36:47,775 --> 00:36:49,856
of high level play in Dota to maximize

840
00:36:49,876 --> 00:36:52,238
your experience point gain relative to your opponents

841
00:36:52,378 --> 00:36:52,979
to out-level them.

842
00:36:53,759 --> 00:36:55,180
However, it's an open question whether

843
00:36:55,260 --> 00:36:56,681
this is actually good design.

844
00:36:57,956 --> 00:37:00,738
At the very least, creep design is accidental design,

845
00:37:00,938 --> 00:37:03,039
because Dota inherited it from Warcraft III.

846
00:37:03,700 --> 00:37:06,401
This was simply how that game handled killing your own units.

847
00:37:06,962 --> 00:37:08,603
Indeed, the fact that Warcraft III even

848
00:37:08,643 --> 00:37:11,064
allowed killing your own units was likely an afterthought

849
00:37:11,084 --> 00:37:11,805
by the designers.

850
00:37:12,765 --> 00:37:17,170
So, Dota inherited this rule because the game was literally built inside of Warcraft 3 as a

851
00:37:17,210 --> 00:37:22,856
mod. Thus, MOBAs inherited a ton of design and mechanics from Warcraft 3. The original

852
00:37:22,896 --> 00:37:27,100
Dota designers may have wanted many things to work differently, but they really didn't have

853
00:37:27,301 --> 00:37:30,845
much of a choice given the limitations and assumptions of the Warcraft 3 editor.

854
00:37:33,442 --> 00:37:40,493
Dota 2 and League of Legends, of course, inherit their design from the original Dota mod, but they made different choices about their inheritance of creep denial.

855
00:37:40,934 --> 00:37:43,458
Basically, League dropped it while Dota 2 kept it.

856
00:37:45,414 --> 00:37:48,577
This is a Reddit thread on why Creep Denial is not in League.

857
00:37:48,637 --> 00:37:53,000
Don't worry about reading this, I just want to point out how a random Dota guy is trying

858
00:37:53,021 --> 00:37:57,104
to explain why Creep Denial is bad for the design using the game mechanics themselves.

859
00:37:57,564 --> 00:38:01,948
This is pretty typical reasoning for something that has become part of a game design's inheritance.

860
00:38:02,448 --> 00:38:06,231
The burden of proof is always on why it should be removed from the game, not on how it got

861
00:38:06,331 --> 00:38:07,232
added in the first place.

862
00:38:07,812 --> 00:38:11,355
However, I have a simpler explanation for why Creep Denial is a bad design.

863
00:38:15,382 --> 00:38:18,806
I mean, come on, you want your players to be spending their time killing their own units?

864
00:38:19,406 --> 00:38:21,769
Is that really a core part of what makes MOBAs work?

865
00:38:22,029 --> 00:38:24,332
The game would fall apart if you couldn't kill your own guys?

866
00:38:26,314 --> 00:38:28,497
Aden perhaps sums it up better than I ever could.

867
00:38:37,410 --> 00:38:40,233
So at some point, you have to step back as a designer

868
00:38:40,313 --> 00:38:41,755
and reevaluate your inheritance.

869
00:38:42,356 --> 00:38:44,679
Does the core gameplay survive without the feature?

870
00:38:45,079 --> 00:38:47,202
Is the feature unintuitive, making the game harder

871
00:38:47,222 --> 00:38:48,363
to understand or to pick up?

872
00:38:48,884 --> 00:38:50,285
Is there a better way for players

873
00:38:50,325 --> 00:38:51,907
to be spending their time than on this feature?

874
00:38:52,804 --> 00:38:56,067
In the case of Creep Denial, the answer to all those questions suggests that the game

875
00:38:56,087 --> 00:38:57,128
would be better off without it.

876
00:38:57,588 --> 00:39:01,631
There is only one magical core feature to MOBAs, the one feature that cannot be dropped,

877
00:39:02,072 --> 00:39:06,575
and that is taking the scope and complexity of an RTS, but focusing the player's controls

878
00:39:06,715 --> 00:39:12,400
onto just one unit, which makes the game accessible to a much larger audience by an order of magnitude.

879
00:39:12,881 --> 00:39:17,604
Everything else, everything else is just accidental inheritance resulting from the game's origin

880
00:39:17,664 --> 00:39:18,605
as a Warcraft 3 mod.

881
00:39:19,717 --> 00:39:23,599
In fact, although League doesn't have creep denial now, they actually started with it.

882
00:39:24,240 --> 00:39:27,542
These are League of Legends' very first patch notes, published in July 2009.

883
00:39:27,602 --> 00:39:33,006
They inherited creep denial, but as you can see, you know, highlighted here, they killed it very

884
00:39:33,126 --> 00:39:37,670
early. So although they got it from the original mod, they were willing to critically examine

885
00:39:37,690 --> 00:39:38,430
their game's past.

886
00:39:40,108 --> 00:39:43,491
In contrast, here's the history of creep denial from Dota 1 to Dota 2.

887
00:39:44,011 --> 00:39:47,454
You can see an awareness that creep denial might not be the best thing for the game.

888
00:39:47,915 --> 00:39:50,597
So look at, like, for instance, 6.82.

889
00:39:51,057 --> 00:39:52,899
Denied creeps now give less experience.

890
00:39:53,399 --> 00:39:57,563
A clear sign that they want to weaken this feature by rewarding players less for focusing

891
00:39:57,623 --> 00:39:58,224
on creep denial.

892
00:39:58,764 --> 00:40:02,147
However, instead of ripping it out, they're making small changes around the edges.

893
00:40:03,710 --> 00:40:06,610
Basically, they're doing what baseball did when they patched

894
00:40:06,670 --> 00:40:09,331
the drop third strike rule by making it not apply in certain

895
00:40:09,371 --> 00:40:11,691
circumstances instead of just getting rid of the rule itself.

896
00:40:12,712 --> 00:40:15,752
Remember my questions on the value of creep denial? Does the

897
00:40:15,772 --> 00:40:18,233
core gameplay survive without the feature? Is the feature

898
00:40:18,293 --> 00:40:20,973
unintuitive, making the game harder to understand or to pick

899
00:40:21,053 --> 00:40:23,354
up? Is there a better way for the players to be spending their

900
00:40:23,374 --> 00:40:26,535
time than on this feature? Running this exercise with the

901
00:40:26,555 --> 00:40:29,735
drop third strike rule gets us to the same place. That is bad

902
00:40:29,855 --> 00:40:32,056
accidental design that is ultimately hurting baseball.

903
00:40:33,990 --> 00:40:36,592
Now here's a comparison of the two games and some other MOBAs.

904
00:40:37,333 --> 00:40:40,656
There are many reasons why League outpaces Dota by an order of magnitude.

905
00:40:41,397 --> 00:40:45,540
An almost three-year head start is a pretty big one, but I also believe that Riot's philosophy

906
00:40:45,560 --> 00:40:50,004
of re-examining their inheritance from the original Dota mod, which extends well beyond

907
00:40:50,045 --> 00:40:52,066
just removing creep denial, is a very important piece.

908
00:40:54,952 --> 00:40:57,152
Now, I also have thoughts about last hitting,

909
00:40:57,413 --> 00:40:59,653
but fortunately, I don't have time for that.

910
00:41:00,554 --> 00:41:03,375
I say fortunately, because Heroes of the Storm, which

911
00:41:03,415 --> 00:41:05,415
is the only one of these three to drop last hitting,

912
00:41:05,656 --> 00:41:07,896
is less successful than Dota 2, let alone League.

913
00:41:08,317 --> 00:41:10,137
Thus, I can't really make an argument

914
00:41:10,177 --> 00:41:12,658
that the market has proven that last hitting is bad design.

915
00:41:13,178 --> 00:41:14,219
Further, I don't think it would be

916
00:41:14,239 --> 00:41:17,440
reasonable to expect Riot to experiment with dropping

917
00:41:17,460 --> 00:41:18,400
last hitting at this point.

918
00:41:19,001 --> 00:41:19,641
It's just too late.

919
00:41:20,261 --> 00:41:22,024
League is one of the world's most popular games.

920
00:41:22,185 --> 00:41:25,611
Indeed, they are lucky that they dropped Creep Denial so early in their development before

921
00:41:25,691 --> 00:41:27,574
doing so might have split community opinion.

922
00:41:29,370 --> 00:41:31,552
We don't always have the luxury of looking at the game

923
00:41:31,592 --> 00:41:33,273
to prove our decisions, which is why

924
00:41:33,373 --> 00:41:34,894
re-examining the game's inheritance

925
00:41:34,914 --> 00:41:36,575
is such a difficult and important issue.

926
00:41:37,256 --> 00:41:38,557
Choosing to erase your inheritance

927
00:41:38,617 --> 00:41:39,638
takes real bravery.

928
00:41:40,158 --> 00:41:43,460
Sometimes you have to trust your own rational design process

929
00:41:43,500 --> 00:41:44,261
if you see a problem.

930
00:41:44,701 --> 00:41:46,042
Sometimes you have to go with your gut.

931
00:41:46,622 --> 00:41:48,604
Ultimately, you must be willing to see your history,

932
00:41:49,004 --> 00:41:50,745
know how it led you to where you are today,

933
00:41:51,085 --> 00:41:52,587
and then have the courage to drop the past.

934
00:41:54,108 --> 00:41:54,348
Thank you.

935
00:42:03,616 --> 00:42:06,757
Next up, our next speaker has been making RPGs

936
00:42:06,797 --> 00:42:08,858
for quite some time, going all the way back to his work

937
00:42:08,918 --> 00:42:11,458
at the illustrious Black Isle Studios on Icewind Dale.

938
00:42:12,119 --> 00:42:14,479
After a stint working near me on a gauntlet game

939
00:42:14,499 --> 00:42:15,379
that we don't need to speak about,

940
00:42:15,419 --> 00:42:18,080
Josh moved on to Obsidian, working on titles like

941
00:42:18,160 --> 00:42:20,501
Fallout, New Vegas, and the Pillars of Eternity series

942
00:42:20,601 --> 00:42:23,202
with Pillars of Eternity 2, Deadfire, Shipping Soon.

943
00:42:23,282 --> 00:42:24,342
I give you Josh Sawyer.

944
00:42:32,639 --> 00:42:32,999
Hello.

945
00:42:33,820 --> 00:42:35,880
By the way, if you want to deal with a nightmare of legacy

946
00:42:35,900 --> 00:42:38,722
design, make a party-based fantasy role-playing game.

947
00:42:42,623 --> 00:42:43,043
For real.

948
00:42:44,624 --> 00:42:47,685
All right, my talk is about how I always try to give 50%,

949
00:42:48,846 --> 00:42:52,568
or how I learned when to stop telling a story and let the

950
00:42:52,588 --> 00:42:53,208
player tell theirs.

951
00:42:57,329 --> 00:42:59,710
If any of you have played in a D&D game,

952
00:43:00,050 --> 00:43:03,031
or run a D&D game, or any sort of tabletop role-playing game,

953
00:43:03,071 --> 00:43:04,472
you have probably had an experience

954
00:43:05,112 --> 00:43:07,553
where your players take the story off of the rails.

955
00:43:08,954 --> 00:43:10,234
A lot of computer role-playing games

956
00:43:10,254 --> 00:43:12,895
try to emulate the tabletop role-playing game environment.

957
00:43:12,935 --> 00:43:14,276
We do this in a lot of different ways.

958
00:43:15,036 --> 00:43:17,037
We can try to emulate the rules themselves.

959
00:43:17,417 --> 00:43:19,218
We can try to emulate the aesthetics.

960
00:43:19,638 --> 00:43:21,499
whether that's in the lore or the visuals of the game.

961
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:24,142
But in a lot of cases, especially at Obsidian,

962
00:43:24,402 --> 00:43:26,524
what we're trying to emulate is player choice,

963
00:43:27,264 --> 00:43:28,706
player choice and player consequence

964
00:43:28,826 --> 00:43:30,107
within the context of a story.

965
00:43:30,467 --> 00:43:31,928
Being able to make your own character,

966
00:43:32,269 --> 00:43:34,390
express that character, and have it

967
00:43:34,511 --> 00:43:35,571
have an impact in the world.

968
00:43:37,758 --> 00:43:41,061
In my experience, playing tabletop games and running tabletop games,

969
00:43:41,461 --> 00:43:44,624
the best dungeon masters and game masters are the ones who improvise.

970
00:43:45,565 --> 00:43:48,988
They construct some idea of a grand story, or maybe they just have parts of a

971
00:43:49,008 --> 00:43:49,969
neat story in their mind,

972
00:43:50,329 --> 00:43:53,172
and when the players screw it up, they don't fight against it.

973
00:43:53,552 --> 00:43:56,735
They let the players go, and they let the story run away,

974
00:43:57,135 --> 00:44:00,378
and everyone has a great time. Because it's a little bit of what the dungeon master

975
00:44:00,418 --> 00:44:02,760
prepared, and it's a lot of what the players brought to it as well.

976
00:44:04,937 --> 00:44:08,620
in a CRPG outside of the mechanical systems, which

977
00:44:08,640 --> 00:44:10,442
is, I think, an interesting contrast.

978
00:44:10,462 --> 00:44:11,563
Because if you look, for example,

979
00:44:11,603 --> 00:44:14,126
at a game like Divinity Original Sin 2, which

980
00:44:14,186 --> 00:44:16,928
is much more oriented around the play of the game

981
00:44:16,968 --> 00:44:18,430
and experimentation with things.

982
00:44:19,171 --> 00:44:21,052
versus something like Pillars of Eternity,

983
00:44:21,092 --> 00:44:23,093
which is more traditional and sort of tabletop based,

984
00:44:23,734 --> 00:44:26,136
we're not there to improvise with the gameplay content.

985
00:44:26,456 --> 00:44:28,838
So what we have to do when we're constructing the story

986
00:44:29,158 --> 00:44:32,200
is effectively try to think about a wide range of players

987
00:44:32,360 --> 00:44:34,982
sitting across from us and imagine the types of things

988
00:44:35,002 --> 00:44:36,183
that they wanna throw back at us.

989
00:44:36,583 --> 00:44:38,625
Ideas about what types of characters they wanna play,

990
00:44:39,465 --> 00:44:41,207
anything from the sort of equipment that they brought,

991
00:44:41,507 --> 00:44:43,088
their background, what spells they have,

992
00:44:43,128 --> 00:44:45,470
what skills they have, if they wanna be an asshole,

