00:44:45,490 --> 00:44:47,811
if they wanna be a smart ass, all of this sort of stuff.

994
00:44:49,049 --> 00:44:50,430
By the way, it's not exactly 50%.

995
00:44:51,011 --> 00:44:52,111
That's just an idea.

996
00:44:54,133 --> 00:44:56,295
So I'd like to talk about some of the ways at Obsidian that

997
00:44:56,335 --> 00:45:01,318
we try to step away from really being strict about how we

998
00:45:01,398 --> 00:45:04,261
author the story and let the player bring their own sort of

999
00:45:04,401 --> 00:45:05,261
ideas into it.

1000
00:45:05,822 --> 00:45:08,424
One of this is trying to eliminate as many critical

1001
00:45:08,484 --> 00:45:11,206
characters as we can from our stories, letting the player

1002
00:45:11,246 --> 00:45:12,447
kill virtually everyone.

1003
00:45:12,887 --> 00:45:14,688
Here are a few examples of this in play.

1004
00:45:15,589 --> 00:45:19,850
The first is Yes Man, Eternal Yes Man from Fall at New Vegas.

1005
00:45:20,571 --> 00:45:23,872
In Fall at New Vegas, you could kill every single character

1006
00:45:23,892 --> 00:45:25,812
in the world except for children.

1007
00:45:27,233 --> 00:45:29,653
And there was one character who was a fall-through character.

1008
00:45:29,713 --> 00:45:30,533
His name was Yes Man.

1009
00:45:30,573 --> 00:45:31,954
He was a robot who would do literally

1010
00:45:31,974 --> 00:45:33,034
whatever you asked him to do.

1011
00:45:33,714 --> 00:45:35,935
And he was the fall-through, so he would help you

1012
00:45:35,975 --> 00:45:36,995
with the independent path.

1013
00:45:37,375 --> 00:45:39,936
And even if you pissed off every single other faction head,

1014
00:45:40,216 --> 00:45:42,677
you could still go back to Yes Man to progress the plot.

1015
00:45:43,217 --> 00:45:44,478
So we wrestled with the idea of, well,

1016
00:45:45,478 --> 00:45:48,919
if he's your fall through and he allows you to get through the plot, how are we going

1017
00:45:48,959 --> 00:45:53,081
to stick to our guns and say, um, let the player kill them? Well, the lucky thing is

1018
00:45:53,121 --> 00:45:57,122
that he's a robot and he's an AI that gets downloaded into other robots. So we actually

1019
00:45:57,162 --> 00:46:01,824
allowed the player to just blast Yes Man right in the face and he would die and then a minute

1020
00:46:01,864 --> 00:46:06,606
later another Securitron robot with his face would roll on up and he would say, I'm sorry,

1021
00:46:06,626 --> 00:46:11,207
I must have made you really angry. I'll try not to do that again in the future. Now how

1022
00:46:11,247 --> 00:46:11,788
can I help you?

1023
00:46:12,968 --> 00:46:19,030
So technically we adhere to this while still allowing the player the agency to pull out whatever weapon they wanted and blowing them away

1024
00:46:19,790 --> 00:46:23,292
And by the way, a lot of players did do this every time they'd go back to talk to yes, man

1025
00:46:23,632 --> 00:46:26,133
They get a new mission objective and they'd say hey, thank you. Thanks, man

1026
00:46:26,293 --> 00:46:30,454
Blam and they'd walk out the door and then they'd come back get a new mission objective. Thanks again. Yes, man

1027
00:46:30,494 --> 00:46:31,455
You're the best Blam

1028
00:46:33,896 --> 00:46:37,657
Another example of this in play is the blood pool from pillars of eternity

1029
00:46:38,697 --> 00:46:41,198
We put a lot of effort into our companions

1030
00:46:42,955 --> 00:46:43,696
Arguably too much.

1031
00:46:44,397 --> 00:46:46,098
We write a lot of companion dialogue.

1032
00:46:46,118 --> 00:46:48,200
We spend a lot of resources on unique character art,

1033
00:46:48,520 --> 00:46:49,982
but we don't require the player

1034
00:46:50,002 --> 00:46:51,543
to take these characters along with them.

1035
00:46:51,843 --> 00:46:53,225
We don't require them individually.

1036
00:46:53,245 --> 00:46:54,386
We don't require them as a group.

1037
00:46:54,466 --> 00:46:56,427
You can play through these games completely by yourself

1038
00:46:56,487 --> 00:46:57,068
if you want to.

1039
00:46:57,648 --> 00:47:01,472
Sometimes you might even really despise a companion.

1040
00:47:01,912 --> 00:47:04,655
So we added the blood pool in Pillars of Eternity.

1041
00:47:05,015 --> 00:47:06,516
It is a pool full of blood.

1042
00:47:07,137 --> 00:47:08,539
dedicated to a crazy god.

1043
00:47:09,079 --> 00:47:12,323
And at the blood pool, you can sacrifice a companion that you really just don't like,

1044
00:47:12,363 --> 00:47:13,604
and you can get a stat boost out of it,

1045
00:47:14,065 --> 00:47:17,489
and every one of your other companions is extremely horrified by what you've just done,

1046
00:47:17,989 --> 00:47:18,790
and you can do it.

1047
00:47:19,171 --> 00:47:22,935
By the way, if you bring your save game into Pillars of Eternity 2 Deadfire,

1048
00:47:23,215 --> 00:47:24,697
we remember that you did that.

1049
00:47:25,418 --> 00:47:26,139
So get ready.

1050
00:47:30,429 --> 00:47:33,111
Some other stuff that we try to do is account for the weird and the funny.

1051
00:47:33,512 --> 00:47:38,215
By the way, this is a place where really we're starting to get away from the idea of system-driven design.

1052
00:47:38,255 --> 00:47:43,559
This is more about, again, these like sort of weird edge cases that you come up with where, you know,

1053
00:47:43,859 --> 00:47:45,780
how many times have you been in a tabletop game?

1054
00:47:46,341 --> 00:47:48,142
I'm just assuming everyone plays a ton of tabletop games.

1055
00:47:48,822 --> 00:47:51,265
And a player tries to do something really weird.

1056
00:47:51,325 --> 00:47:53,867
They have some desperate, like, they have some item

1057
00:47:53,907 --> 00:47:55,669
they try to use in some last ditch effort,

1058
00:47:56,229 --> 00:47:58,411
and they manage to save the day, and it's really great.

1059
00:47:58,811 --> 00:48:00,473
So we try to figure out ways to account

1060
00:48:00,493 --> 00:48:02,154
for these really weird situations.

1061
00:48:02,515 --> 00:48:04,737
It's a niche of a niche, but when players find it,

1062
00:48:05,397 --> 00:48:07,559
and we hope that a player will find one of these things

1063
00:48:07,579 --> 00:48:09,561
in every playthrough, they feel really rewarded

1064
00:48:09,621 --> 00:48:11,863
for just carrying some stupid crap around with them

1065
00:48:11,923 --> 00:48:13,325
or picking one special background

1066
00:48:13,345 --> 00:48:14,926
that comes up in a really cool circumstance.

1067
00:48:16,065 --> 00:48:18,406
One example is the corpse checker from Icewind Dale 2.

1068
00:48:19,426 --> 00:48:21,327
One of our designers at the time, Damian Filetto,

1069
00:48:21,787 --> 00:48:25,988
he realized that there were three quests in the game that

1070
00:48:26,048 --> 00:48:28,009
required you to carry around a dead body.

1071
00:48:29,550 --> 00:48:31,250
And we never got rid of those dead bodies.

1072
00:48:31,330 --> 00:48:34,371
So you could be carrying around a dead man, a dead woman,

1073
00:48:34,731 --> 00:48:35,432
and a dead cat.

1074
00:48:37,310 --> 00:48:38,130
They weighed a ton.

1075
00:48:38,190 --> 00:48:40,051
There was no reason to carry these things around,

1076
00:48:40,131 --> 00:48:41,891
but some players kept carrying these things around.

1077
00:48:42,531 --> 00:48:43,772
So at the end of the game, there was

1078
00:48:43,812 --> 00:48:45,132
a character who would start talking to you

1079
00:48:45,152 --> 00:48:46,352
in the middle of his dialogue.

1080
00:48:46,372 --> 00:48:50,854
He would go, are you carrying around three dead bodies?

1081
00:48:51,554 --> 00:48:53,114
Are you a crazy person?

1082
00:48:53,154 --> 00:48:55,255
And he would start going off, and he's like, wait a minute.

1083
00:48:55,275 --> 00:48:56,695
I think maybe I've underestimated you.

1084
00:48:56,975 --> 00:48:58,156
I don't think I really want to mess with you.

1085
00:48:58,196 --> 00:48:58,536
You know what?

1086
00:48:58,856 --> 00:48:59,996
You can just go off on your own.

1087
00:49:00,076 --> 00:49:01,037
It'll be totally fine.

1088
00:49:01,097 --> 00:49:03,878
And it was just, again, this weird little niche

1089
00:49:03,918 --> 00:49:06,638
thing for people who decided to carry three corpses around

1090
00:49:06,678 --> 00:49:06,878
with a son.

1091
00:49:08,900 --> 00:49:11,021
The Psycho Squad in Fallout New Vegas,

1092
00:49:11,061 --> 00:49:13,562
there is a quest called Flags of Our Foul Ups

1093
00:49:14,462 --> 00:49:15,902
written by Travis Stout.

1094
00:49:16,722 --> 00:49:19,443
And there is a group of soldiers called Misfits.

1095
00:49:19,503 --> 00:49:21,503
They were horribly incompetent NCR soldiers.

1096
00:49:22,244 --> 00:49:23,984
And they were trying to get into shape.

1097
00:49:24,684 --> 00:49:26,065
And you could train them.

1098
00:49:26,165 --> 00:49:27,405
You could go the normal way.

1099
00:49:27,465 --> 00:49:28,965
You could teach them to throw a grenade,

1100
00:49:28,985 --> 00:49:30,626
teach them to shoot a gun, teach them all these things

1101
00:49:30,646 --> 00:49:32,706
that you need to know so that they weren't huge screw-ups.

1102
00:49:33,466 --> 00:49:36,407
Or if you were carrying around an enormous amount of psycho

1103
00:49:37,047 --> 00:49:39,308
which is a combat drug that makes you go crazy.

1104
00:49:39,589 --> 00:49:41,330
You could say, you don't need to be good soldiers.

1105
00:49:41,370 --> 00:49:42,450
Just take a bunch of this drug.

1106
00:49:43,271 --> 00:49:45,192
And that would actually resolve the quest for you.

1107
00:49:45,272 --> 00:49:46,372
And they'd be like, wow, awesome.

1108
00:49:46,412 --> 00:49:47,453
All we got to do is take this drug?

1109
00:49:47,473 --> 00:49:48,113
That's really great.

1110
00:49:48,493 --> 00:49:50,434
So you would resolve the quest and go on your merry way.

1111
00:49:50,514 --> 00:49:53,696
And then at the end of the game, they actually performed really

1112
00:49:53,736 --> 00:49:54,516
well in combat.

1113
00:49:54,917 --> 00:49:56,958
And then they went on a murderous spree.

1114
00:49:57,198 --> 00:49:58,859
And they wound up being hung for war crimes.

1115
00:49:59,379 --> 00:49:59,919
So this is a.

1116
00:50:01,341 --> 00:50:03,362
We always try to have these long-term payoffs

1117
00:50:03,422 --> 00:50:05,323
for these little things that the player can do,

1118
00:50:05,643 --> 00:50:08,125
in this case, carrying around, I think it was like 25 doses

1119
00:50:08,165 --> 00:50:10,326
of Psycho, which is really sort of excessive.

1120
00:50:12,587 --> 00:50:15,008
And then finally, Eric Fenstermaker's know-it-all

1121
00:50:15,048 --> 00:50:17,009
nihilist from Pillars of Eternity.

1122
00:50:18,130 --> 00:50:19,811
Eric Fenstermaker was really a champion

1123
00:50:20,091 --> 00:50:22,472
of letting the player establish their background

1124
00:50:22,592 --> 00:50:24,353
and then develop it early on in the game

1125
00:50:24,393 --> 00:50:26,554
so they could really get a sense of who they are.

1126
00:50:27,575 --> 00:50:28,795
This ties into another point that I'm

1127
00:50:28,815 --> 00:50:29,716
going to go into in a second.

1128
00:50:30,156 --> 00:50:31,937
So if you took the philosopher background,

1129
00:50:32,457 --> 00:50:34,598
you could talk to this character Kalisha in the early game,

1130
00:50:34,618 --> 00:50:36,479
and you could say, yeah, I'm a philosopher,

1131
00:50:36,519 --> 00:50:37,780
and I believe this, or I believe that.

1132
00:50:37,840 --> 00:50:38,740
And one of the things you could say is,

1133
00:50:38,760 --> 00:50:40,501
like, I don't really believe in anything.

1134
00:50:40,541 --> 00:50:41,782
I believe this is all an illusion.

1135
00:50:41,822 --> 00:50:42,822
This is a bunch of fakery.

1136
00:50:43,162 --> 00:50:44,883
And that sort of marks your character as a nihilist.

1137
00:50:44,923 --> 00:50:47,044
And it came up maybe a couple more times throughout the game.

1138
00:50:47,524 --> 00:50:49,025
There's a Pillars of Eternity spoiler here.

1139
00:50:49,485 --> 00:50:49,785
Sorry.

1140
00:50:50,266 --> 00:50:51,866
So at the end of the game, when it's

1141
00:50:51,946 --> 00:50:54,288
revealed that the gods are not real,

1142
00:50:54,528 --> 00:50:56,349
if you picked the nihilist background,

1143
00:50:56,609 --> 00:50:58,470
you get a special line that says, I knew it.

1144
00:51:01,881 --> 00:51:04,203
Again, this is these accounting for the weird and the funny

1145
00:51:04,243 --> 00:51:05,304
things that the players pick.

1146
00:51:07,626 --> 00:51:10,969
So sometimes it's important to just ask the player why

1147
00:51:11,009 --> 00:51:11,909
they're doing what they're doing.

1148
00:51:12,210 --> 00:51:14,432
I mean, ask it narratively within the context of the game,

1149
00:51:14,472 --> 00:51:16,653
not as the designer themselves.

1150
00:51:17,594 --> 00:51:18,855
So why ask the player why?

1151
00:51:18,935 --> 00:51:20,837
Because it makes them ask themselves why.

1152
00:51:20,997 --> 00:51:22,318
Why am I doing the things that I'm doing?

1153
00:51:23,949 --> 00:51:25,811
One of the first examples is the Animancy Trial

1154
00:51:25,891 --> 00:51:26,772
in Pillars of Eternity.

1155
00:51:27,232 --> 00:51:30,015
So you are given exposure to animancy,

1156
00:51:30,055 --> 00:51:31,597
which is the science of reading souls

1157
00:51:31,637 --> 00:51:33,018
within the Pillars of Eternity universe.

1158
00:51:33,899 --> 00:51:35,520
It's used for some good things.

1159
00:51:35,841 --> 00:51:37,702
Very often it's used for some really bad things.

1160
00:51:38,203 --> 00:51:39,204
A lot of characters in the world

1161
00:51:39,224 --> 00:51:40,185
have different opinions on it,

1162
00:51:40,325 --> 00:51:41,846
and by the time you get to this point in the game,

1163
00:51:42,167 --> 00:51:43,668
you've really seen a lot of these examples,

1164
00:51:44,008 --> 00:51:46,070
and you're asked, because of your experiences,

1165
00:51:46,090 --> 00:51:47,872
to testify to the Duke.

1166
00:51:48,232 --> 00:51:50,133
about what you think about animancy.

1167
00:51:50,433 --> 00:51:52,573
And this is a way to really get the player to think about,

1168
00:51:52,933 --> 00:51:54,473
well, you know, I've been kind of playing through the game

1169
00:51:54,493 --> 00:51:55,434
and I've seen all of these things,

1170
00:51:55,454 --> 00:51:56,654
but what do I really think about it?

1171
00:51:56,954 --> 00:51:59,194
And obviously you can only account for so many opinions,

1172
00:51:59,514 --> 00:52:01,255
but it is a nice way to make the player go like,

1173
00:52:01,355 --> 00:52:03,415
okay, well, I'm playing this character and I've seen this,

1174
00:52:03,435 --> 00:52:04,495
so well, I think this.

1175
00:52:05,156 --> 00:52:07,896
And it just helps really sort of ground the character

1176
00:52:07,916 --> 00:52:10,077
and their understanding of who they are in this world

1177
00:52:10,177 --> 00:52:11,297
and being able to express it

1178
00:52:11,337 --> 00:52:13,057
instead of just having it inside their head.

1179
00:52:14,825 --> 00:52:17,447
Another example is Arcade in Fallout New Vegas.

1180
00:52:17,567 --> 00:52:19,988
I apologize that I don't have any credit for this art.

1181
00:52:20,028 --> 00:52:20,908
I found it on Tumblr.

1182
00:52:21,328 --> 00:52:23,449
And as you know, if you try to find the original source

1183
00:52:23,469 --> 00:52:25,950
of something on Tumblr, you will never find it.

1184
00:52:27,751 --> 00:52:29,972
So Arcade in Fallout New Vegas is a character

1185
00:52:30,012 --> 00:52:30,972
who is pretty moral.

1186
00:52:31,413 --> 00:52:32,673
He's with the followers of the apocalypse.

1187
00:52:32,793 --> 00:52:36,475
And if you go to Caesar's Legion, to Caesar's camp,

1188
00:52:36,815 --> 00:52:37,935
Caesar is a crazy dictator.

1189
00:52:38,476 --> 00:52:39,876
And Arcade stops you, and he's like.

1190
00:52:40,840 --> 00:52:42,321
What in the world are we doing?

1191
00:52:42,361 --> 00:52:44,601
We're accepting an invitation from a dictator

1192
00:52:44,621 --> 00:52:45,502
to go over and talk to him.

1193
00:52:45,522 --> 00:52:46,422
He enslaves people.

1194
00:52:46,482 --> 00:52:48,763
He's torturing and crucifying all these people.

1195
00:52:48,803 --> 00:52:50,223
What could you possibly hope to get out

1196
00:52:50,243 --> 00:52:51,183
of talking with this guy?

1197
00:52:51,863 --> 00:52:53,844
And this conversation is partially a way

1198
00:52:53,924 --> 00:52:57,765
for you to try to either mollify, arcade,

1199
00:52:57,985 --> 00:53:01,446
or to maybe just think about it yourself.

1200
00:53:01,506 --> 00:53:03,086
Like, well, what am I trying to get out of this?

1201
00:53:03,927 --> 00:53:08,570
You know, you got an invitation and so you're doing a quest, but are you doing it because you really want to hear him out?

1202
00:53:08,650 --> 00:53:11,431
Are you doing it because you want to get some sort of advantage with him in the future?

1203
00:53:11,451 --> 00:53:12,852
Do you want to get close to him?

1204
00:53:13,372 --> 00:53:17,555
This is a way again of getting the player to really think about the motivations for why they're doing what they're doing.

1205
00:53:18,876 --> 00:53:22,418
By the way, there are sacrifices to doing all this crazy stuff.

1206
00:53:24,364 --> 00:53:25,145
It is a lot of work.

1207
00:53:26,906 --> 00:53:28,867
We write a lot of dialogue, and a lot of that dialogue

1208
00:53:28,907 --> 00:53:31,429
comes down to making choices available to the player.

1209
00:53:31,829 --> 00:53:34,211
Also, when you allow people to just kill everyone,

1210
00:53:34,351 --> 00:53:35,452
you do have to handle that.

1211
00:53:35,612 --> 00:53:37,713
It's a lot easier to just say, no, this character

1212
00:53:37,753 --> 00:53:38,354
is invulnerable.

1213
00:53:38,394 --> 00:53:39,354
You don't have to deal with them.

1214
00:53:39,855 --> 00:53:43,957
In Pillars of Maturity 2, we actually have faction heads.

1215
00:53:43,997 --> 00:53:47,079
So we have four factions, and we have multiple faction heads

1216
00:53:47,139 --> 00:53:48,400
for each faction, and we keep them

1217
00:53:48,440 --> 00:53:50,762
separated in different scenes to prevent the killer from taking

1218
00:53:50,842 --> 00:53:53,704
or the player, sorry, the player who is a, the player.

1219
00:53:57,020 --> 00:54:02,183
who is a murderer, from wiping them both out in one fell swoop.

1220
00:54:02,984 --> 00:54:05,045
So you do have to do a lot of work thinking

1221
00:54:05,085 --> 00:54:06,966
about all the contingencies for this stuff,

1222
00:54:06,986 --> 00:54:08,367
because it's not systemically driven.

1223
00:54:08,487 --> 00:54:09,587
It's all custom content.

1224
00:54:11,368 --> 00:54:14,370
If you want to make a hero's journey, goodbye.

1225
00:54:14,390 --> 00:54:17,992
It's not really great if you're trying

1226
00:54:18,012 --> 00:54:19,292
to make this big emergent thing.

1227
00:54:19,833 --> 00:54:22,374
It does not survive the process, because players love

1228
00:54:22,394 --> 00:54:23,775
screwing with hero's journeys.

1229
00:54:25,067 --> 00:54:29,191
The scale and the scope of the impact of the choices that you make, especially if you litter the game with it,

1230
00:54:29,551 --> 00:54:32,054
has to be, by its very nature, relatively small.

1231
00:54:32,454 --> 00:54:35,897
If you want it to be all over the place, it can't be earth-shattering.

1232
00:54:36,898 --> 00:54:42,743
So you have to try to take solace in the fact that you have a very rich game with lots of little outcomes.

1233
00:54:43,144 --> 00:54:47,528
If you try to make massive changes at every fork in the road, it's going to take you forever.

1234
00:54:48,843 --> 00:54:51,164
Also, you need to think about the scope of player voice,

1235
00:54:51,224 --> 00:54:52,044
motive, and identity.

1236
00:54:52,404 --> 00:54:54,865
When you allow people to play a wide range of characters

1237
00:54:54,905 --> 00:54:57,586
from beatific saints to psychotic murderers,

1238
00:54:58,866 --> 00:55:01,227
your player voice is going to have to cover a range.

1239
00:55:01,547 --> 00:55:02,967
And you have to decide as an author

1240
00:55:03,367 --> 00:55:05,348
how wide you wanna make that range be.

1241
00:55:05,828 --> 00:55:07,688
Because you can't account for everything.

1242
00:55:07,748 --> 00:55:09,149
You can't account for every single thing

1243
00:55:09,169 --> 00:55:09,909
the player can do.

1244
00:55:10,249 --> 00:55:11,369
You shouldn't try to do that.

1245
00:55:11,649 --> 00:55:13,230
What you should try to do is think about it

1246
00:55:13,350 --> 00:55:14,630
from the player's perspective.

1247
00:55:14,930 --> 00:55:17,231
Think about the person sitting across the table

1248
00:55:17,531 --> 00:55:17,871
playing D&D.

1249
00:55:18,651 --> 00:55:20,557
and what they might want to bring into the story

1250
00:55:20,597 --> 00:55:21,941
that you've created a framework for.

1251
00:55:22,984 --> 00:55:23,967
