1301
00:57:39,090 --> 00:57:40,571
if you're interested in checking that out later.

1302
00:57:41,448 --> 00:57:44,050
All right, so first of all, this is what not to do.

1303
00:57:44,731 --> 00:57:45,912
So I thought I'd get that out of the way.

1304
00:57:46,352 --> 00:57:47,312
Sometimes when people think, like,

1305
00:57:47,352 --> 00:57:50,315
I'm gonna make a paper prototype of my computer game,

1306
00:57:50,695 --> 00:57:53,437
so let's make every unit, the entire campaign,

1307
00:57:53,477 --> 00:57:55,298
and add in an expansion pack while we're at it,

1308
00:57:55,378 --> 00:57:56,939
and let's just try to make this

1309
00:57:57,019 --> 00:57:59,261
the most complete thing we can possibly get.

1310
00:58:00,041 --> 00:58:01,182
But actually, the truth is you need

1311
00:58:01,202 --> 00:58:02,524
to do the opposite of that.

1312
00:58:02,584 --> 00:58:04,245
You need to make it as small as possible

1313
00:58:04,285 --> 00:58:05,887
and then make it smaller after you've figured out

1314
00:58:05,907 --> 00:58:06,768
what that small is.

1315
00:58:06,788 --> 00:58:10,011
So let me talk about four different ways that I

1316
00:58:10,051 --> 00:58:11,112
kind of think about the problem.

1317
00:58:11,993 --> 00:58:14,135
So first of all is state your intention.

1318
00:58:14,195 --> 00:58:16,357
Why are you even making this prototype in the first place?

1319
00:58:17,399 --> 00:58:21,522
What is the key question that you're trying to answer by building this?

1320
00:58:21,542 --> 00:58:22,903
And there could be a lot of reasons for this.

1321
00:58:22,923 --> 00:58:25,526
It might just be something that people on the team are asking,

1322
00:58:25,546 --> 00:58:26,587
that they're confused about.

1323
00:58:27,227 --> 00:58:30,390
Might be a question that you have yourself, but the game's just not far

1324
00:58:30,430 --> 00:58:34,093
enough along in development for you to be able to answer that with the game.

1325
00:58:34,233 --> 00:58:36,195
And so this might be a way of jump starting or

1326
00:58:36,415 --> 00:58:38,237
bootstrapping the process really quickly.

1327
00:58:39,413 --> 00:58:41,733
And the second thing is, what's the scope

1328
00:58:42,134 --> 00:58:43,994
that you're going to be trying to tackle?

1329
00:58:44,034 --> 00:58:45,875
Like, how much of the game are you going to try to do?

1330
00:58:46,655 --> 00:58:48,815
And like I said, it's like the smaller is probably the better.

1331
00:58:49,275 --> 00:58:51,996
So just one simple idea, like maybe you

1332
00:58:52,016 --> 00:58:53,937
want to know how much potions should cost

1333
00:58:53,957 --> 00:58:56,777
or how often the potion should restock in the store.

1334
00:58:57,178 --> 00:59:01,459
So very specific, very key question, part of the game,

1335
00:59:02,679 --> 00:59:03,939
just to see how that might work out.

1336
00:59:05,080 --> 00:59:06,220
Maybe you want to expand a little bit more

1337
00:59:06,260 --> 00:59:07,040
and go for a session.

1338
00:59:07,760 --> 00:59:12,202
session might be let's say you're doing a farming game and the the fall season's coming up and you want to know how people are

1339
00:59:12,222 --> 00:59:13,463
going to allocate resources

1340
00:59:13,483 --> 00:59:18,005
So you can make a little game that kind of tests out what kind of resources you would need and how many there might be

1341
00:59:18,025 --> 00:59:23,267
Now you can go out and do the full game and unlike the StarCraft example that I just gave

1342
00:59:23,687 --> 00:59:27,209
When I said the full game, it's gonna be a very narrow slice of the full game

1343
00:59:28,010 --> 00:59:34,738
So in this example here, it's like maybe I'm just curious about how players will allocate skill points as they go from the beginning of the game to level 50.

1344
00:59:35,339 --> 00:59:42,608
And so we're going to go through the entire game, but we're only just going to be looking at a very simple system, which is how skill points are allocated.

1345
00:59:43,618 --> 00:59:45,579
And finally, maybe you're going beyond that.

1346
00:59:45,619 --> 00:59:46,759
You were just wondering about the metagame.

1347
00:59:46,779 --> 00:59:48,499
You don't really even care about the actual game.

1348
00:59:48,880 --> 00:59:51,480
You want to know about the reward systems that happen

1349
00:59:51,520 --> 00:59:55,022
between each game and how the player may, say if it's a deck

1350
00:59:55,042 --> 00:59:57,602
building game, how they may modify their deck as new cards

1351
00:59:57,642 --> 00:59:59,823
come into the environment, their choices change, and

1352
00:59:59,843 --> 01:00:00,663
their options change.

1353
01:00:02,472 --> 01:00:05,232
The third thing is really to specify the purpose.

1354
01:00:05,892 --> 01:00:07,093
Why are you making this thing?

1355
01:00:07,113 --> 01:00:08,353
What are you really trying to get out of it?

1356
01:00:09,513 --> 01:00:11,754
So one thing that's kind of common

1357
01:00:11,794 --> 01:00:13,694
is like I just want to do this mechanical simulation.

1358
01:00:13,754 --> 01:00:16,615
I can't play it yet, so I'm just going to pretend to play it.

1359
01:00:17,275 --> 01:00:18,915
And I kind of caution against this

1360
01:00:18,995 --> 01:00:21,116
because computers are really good at doing this

1361
01:00:21,176 --> 01:00:22,416
and paper's terrible at doing it.

1362
01:00:22,976 --> 01:00:24,397
But it can still come into play at times.

1363
01:00:24,457 --> 01:00:25,257
It still can kind of work.

1364
01:00:25,297 --> 01:00:29,298
If you're really concerned about distances, cause and effects

1365
01:00:29,338 --> 01:00:30,798
relationships, things like that, you

1366
01:00:30,818 --> 01:00:32,018
can kind of mock these things up.

1367
01:00:33,059 --> 01:00:37,584
The opposite of that would be something very abstract, where this is something a player will never see.

1368
01:00:38,085 --> 01:00:42,810
It doesn't actually occur anywhere in the game, but it's a way for you to get information about the game

1369
01:00:42,830 --> 01:00:46,955
and how the players are going to perceive the different systems from a very high level.

1370
01:00:47,455 --> 01:00:49,738
So the player may be down in the game, but you want to know everything.

1371
01:00:50,299 --> 01:00:53,763
In this case, maybe it's the relationship between monsters and weapons.

1372
01:00:55,804 --> 01:00:57,705
And maybe you're just concerned about the emotional engagement.

1373
01:00:58,005 --> 01:00:59,326
You want to know how players are going to feel,

1374
01:00:59,346 --> 01:01:01,088
how they're going to respond to certain events.

1375
01:01:01,548 --> 01:01:03,089
So say we're making a skateboarding game

1376
01:01:03,109 --> 01:01:04,210
and there's a combo system.

1377
01:01:04,570 --> 01:01:06,492
Are players going to laugh when they fail the combo?

1378
01:01:06,512 --> 01:01:07,833
Are they going to get frustrated?

1379
01:01:08,253 --> 01:01:09,894
What kind of surprises are going to occur?

1380
01:01:10,595 --> 01:01:12,616
Are they really cheering together at the same time?

1381
01:01:12,997 --> 01:01:15,098
And so you can kind of gauge the reactions in that way

1382
01:01:15,178 --> 01:01:15,779
from the players.

1383
01:01:16,840 --> 01:01:18,982
And then the fourth thing is the time scale.

1384
01:01:20,003 --> 01:01:23,147
How relative to what the actual game will be running,

1385
01:01:23,327 --> 01:01:24,709
what is your paper prototype?

1386
01:01:24,729 --> 01:01:25,650
How's that going to be working?

1387
01:01:26,050 --> 01:01:28,253
And so it's a pretty common case that it's going to be

1388
01:01:28,433 --> 01:01:31,556
much slower than the game that you're working on, the

1389
01:01:31,596 --> 01:01:32,557
intended time scale.

1390
01:01:33,218 --> 01:01:35,561
And this might be a case of, let's say you're working on a

1391
01:01:35,601 --> 01:01:37,864
shooter game, and you want to understand player decisions

1392
01:01:37,904 --> 01:01:40,467
and reactions, and how they respond to different events.

1393
01:01:40,487 --> 01:01:41,628
So you make this little card game.

1394
01:01:41,988 --> 01:01:44,752
Maybe each card takes a minute to play while people think

1395
01:01:44,792 --> 01:01:46,874
about it, but in the actual game, it's a second while they

1396
01:01:46,894 --> 01:01:48,036
pull the trigger or push the button.

1397
01:01:49,494 --> 01:01:51,455
You can go real time as well.

1398
01:01:51,475 --> 01:01:52,836
Again, this is a little dangerous.

1399
01:01:52,856 --> 01:01:53,936
Computers are great at this.

1400
01:01:54,497 --> 01:01:56,598
So maybe it's just better to do this in the computer.

1401
01:01:57,238 --> 01:01:59,459
But I have seen some examples where you just

1402
01:01:59,479 --> 01:02:00,680
want to test reaction time.

1403
01:02:01,080 --> 01:02:03,081
You want to see if a player is under pressure,

1404
01:02:03,842 --> 01:02:05,923
how does that change their decision making process?

1405
01:02:06,463 --> 01:02:09,585
Are they able to still make great decisions or really

1406
01:02:09,625 --> 01:02:12,727
crippled decisions based on the time constraints

1407
01:02:12,747 --> 01:02:13,547
that you're putting on them?

1408
01:02:14,869 --> 01:02:17,810
And then it's also kind of common to do the faster, where

1409
01:02:18,250 --> 01:02:20,792
your game is going to play out much, much faster than the

1410
01:02:20,912 --> 01:02:22,513
actual game, the video game.

1411
01:02:22,593 --> 01:02:25,675
So let's say I'm making a campaign-style game where

1412
01:02:25,695 --> 01:02:29,377
these tribes are attacking each other, and the main part

1413
01:02:29,397 --> 01:02:30,477
of the game might be the battles.

1414
01:02:31,198 --> 01:02:33,099
But I'm going to just simulate those with a simple die roll,

1415
01:02:34,540 --> 01:02:37,721
because I really want to see how the continent is used, how

1416
01:02:37,761 --> 01:02:40,403
the land is used, as the tribes start to spread out

1417
01:02:40,443 --> 01:02:41,043
across the world.

1418
01:02:42,400 --> 01:02:44,561
All right, so those are kind of like the four things.

1419
01:02:44,581 --> 01:02:46,582
Like, why am I even making this paper prototype?

1420
01:02:47,362 --> 01:02:48,983
Where is it happening in the game?

1421
01:02:49,763 --> 01:02:51,864
What's the purpose that I'm trying to get out of this?

1422
01:02:52,084 --> 01:02:54,945
And then the when, like what part of the time

1423
01:02:55,005 --> 01:02:56,026
is that really happening?

1424
01:02:56,746 --> 01:02:58,487
So those are all kind of little toy examples that I gave.

1425
01:02:58,507 --> 01:02:59,847
So let me give some real examples here.

1426
01:02:59,867 --> 01:03:01,288
I'll kind of end up with five of these.

1427
01:03:02,188 --> 01:03:05,351
And this one is from when I worked at Blizzard North.

1428
01:03:05,431 --> 01:03:09,455
We were on the Diablo team, but we were asked by Blizzard South

1429
01:03:09,495 --> 01:03:11,757
and Irvine if we could come up with a card game that would

1430
01:03:11,777 --> 01:03:12,978
appear in World of Warcraft.

1431
01:03:13,739 --> 01:03:15,621
And the idea would be that you would kill a monster in World

1432
01:03:15,641 --> 01:03:17,442
of Warcraft, and it might drop a trading card.

1433
01:03:17,723 --> 01:03:19,284
And if you collect enough of these cards, you could build a

1434
01:03:19,324 --> 01:03:21,206
deck, and then you would go into a tavern, and you would

1435
01:03:21,226 --> 01:03:23,428
play this tavern game inside of World of Warcraft.

1436
01:03:24,129 --> 01:03:24,489
Never got.

1437
01:03:25,029 --> 01:03:26,170
Picked up they ran out of time to do it

1438
01:03:26,250 --> 01:03:32,536
But that didn't stop us from making hundreds of these cards and playing this game at lunch pretty much every day for a couple a couple

1439
01:03:32,576 --> 01:03:32,836
months

1440
01:03:34,137 --> 01:03:37,140
So for this one the intention is just mentioned. It's like what would that card game be?

1441
01:03:37,220 --> 01:03:39,221
How could you play it in a tavern inside of WoW?

1442
01:03:40,162 --> 01:03:44,546
Our scope was session based that we were trying to figure out like what a session of this game would play like

1443
01:03:45,126 --> 01:03:49,710
But we're also really interested in the metagame like again how the cards would change over time as we introduced

1444
01:03:50,010 --> 01:03:51,532
new factions and things into the sets

1445
01:03:52,352 --> 01:03:53,733
a very mechanical simulation.

1446
01:03:53,773 --> 01:03:55,195
It played out a little bit slower

1447
01:03:55,335 --> 01:03:56,115
than what we'd expect.

1448
01:03:56,175 --> 01:03:58,677
It's a card game in WoW and a card game in real life.

1449
01:03:59,338 --> 01:04:00,299
So they're fairly close.

1450
01:04:00,379 --> 01:04:02,760
But when the computer shuffles for you and keeps track of

1451
01:04:02,780 --> 01:04:05,362
status effects and the like, the game actually would play a

1452
01:04:05,383 --> 01:04:06,343
lot faster on the computer.

1453
01:04:08,009 --> 01:04:10,352
This is another one, Never Saw the Light of Day.

1454
01:04:10,632 --> 01:04:14,956
This is from Blizzard North where we were looking for something to do besides Diablo.

1455
01:04:15,477 --> 01:04:21,382
So we decided to make, pitch an idea that would be Diablo but set in the StarCraft universe.

1456
01:04:21,422 --> 01:04:23,024
So science fiction Diablo if you would.

1457
01:04:23,044 --> 01:04:23,925
We call it Starblow.

1458
01:04:24,325 --> 01:04:25,206
Not the best name.

1459
01:04:28,348 --> 01:04:30,608
So one part of that was figuring out, what are all the weapons?

1460
01:04:30,628 --> 01:04:32,349
You know, Diablo's a lot about collecting all these items.

1461
01:04:32,369 --> 01:04:33,489
So what would these weapon sets be?

1462
01:04:33,529 --> 01:04:34,210
How would they all work?

1463
01:04:34,530 --> 01:04:37,030
And so I made these little trading cards and they were outside my office.

1464
01:04:37,070 --> 01:04:39,791
And originally they were all blank, like the two that you see in the middle.

1465
01:04:40,551 --> 01:04:44,313
But I told the artists that if you give me art, I'll put it on the card and I'll put

1466
01:04:44,333 --> 01:04:46,433
your name on it as the illustrator of the card.

1467
01:04:46,453 --> 01:04:49,934
And that started this little kind of competition among the artists, like grab the cool weapons

1468
01:04:49,974 --> 01:04:53,355
